{"pageid": 3, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory1-tab9", "text": "**Summation notation**  The [mathjaxinline]\\sum[/mathjaxinline] notation is a compact way to denote a sum in which each term is obtained from a formula:    [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\sum _{i=1}^ n a_ i = a_1+a_2+\\cdots +a_{n-1}+a_{n}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] indexes the terms, and [mathjaxinline]a_ i[/mathjaxinline] is a formula for the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] term of the sum.   The notation [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sum _{i=1}^ n a_ i[/mathjaxinline] reads \u201cthe sum of [mathjaxinline]a_ i[/mathjaxinline] from [mathjaxinline]i=1[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]i=n[/mathjaxinline].\"    For example, if [mathjaxinline]a_ i=i^2[/mathjaxinline], that is, the formula for the term indexed by [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]i^2[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\sum _{i=1}^ n i^2 = 1^2+2^2+3^2+\\cdots +(n-1)^2+n^2[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This notation is a shorthand to write a potentially very long sum, but it does not simplify any calculations.  Summation notation", "filename": "theory1-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Summation notation"}

{"pageid": 4, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_2-tab7", "text": "**The indefinite integral**  Given a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline], the royalblue **indefinite integral** or royalblue **the antiderivative** of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is denoted [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int f(x) dx[/mathjaxinline]. It is the family of functions  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int f(x) \\, dx \\, = F(x) + C[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\ F(x)[/mathjaxinline] is any antiderivative of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline], that is, [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ F'(x)=f(x)[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline] is any constant.    We call [mathjaxinline]\\int[/mathjaxinline] the royalblue **integral sign** , [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] the royalblue **integrand** , and [mathjaxinline]\\, C[/mathjaxinline] the royalblue **constant of integration**.    Let us explain the presence of the constant of integration in geometric terms. The derivative of a function determines only the shape of the function, but the derivative does not change if the function is shifted up or down by the same constant everywhere.    Indefinite integral", "filename": "antider_2-tab7-text2.html", "title": "Indefinite integral"}

{"pageid": 5, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications4-tab5", "text": "**Trapezoidal Rule**  To approximate the integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline]:    * Subdivide the interval into [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] pieces [mathjaxinline]a = x_0 < x_1 < \\dotsb < x_{n-1} < x_ n = b[/mathjaxinline].     * Let [mathjaxinline]y_0 = f(x_0)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]y_1 = f(x_1)[/mathjaxinline], ... , [mathjaxinline]y_{n-1}= f(x_{n-1})[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]y_ n = f(x_ n)[/mathjaxinline].     * [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x = \\displaystyle \\frac{b-a}{n}[/mathjaxinline].     * **Trapezoidal Rule** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx \\approx \\Delta x\\left( \\frac12 y_0 + y_1 + \\dotsb + y_{n-1} + \\frac12 y_ n \\right).[/mathjaxinline]   Trapezoidal Rule", "filename": "applications4-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Trapezoidal Rule"}

{"pageid": 6, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications2-tab11", "text": "In the cauldron example, heat energy is transferred to the water in the cauldron. bordeaux **Heat** is defined as the energy required to raise the temperature of an object. So we want to measure the heat required to change the temperature of the water. How do we do this?  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\underbrace{\\text {Heat energy}}_{\\text {cal}} = \\underbrace{\\text {(Volume)}}_{\\text {mL}} \\cdot \\underbrace{\\text {(Temperature)}}_{{}^{\\circ {}} \\text {Celsius}}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Some units needed in this problem:    * A bordeaux **calorie** is the amount of energy required to heat one gram of water 1 degree Celsius.     * A bordeaux **kilocalorie** is the amount of energy required to heat one kilogram of water 1 degree Celsius.     * One bordeaux **milliliter** of water weighs one gram.     * One bordeaux **cubic centimeter** is one bordeaux **milliliter**.   ### What is Halloween?  Halloween is a US holiday on October 31 where kids dress up in costumes and go door to door asking for candy via the phrase \u201ctrick or treat\" implying they will either take a treat or trick the person.  Physics background", "filename": "applications2-tab11-text1.html", "title": "Physics background"}

{"pageid": 7, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory2-tab23", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/ftc1_summary.pdf)   **The First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus**  The bordeaux **First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus** states that:   If [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] is differentiable, and [mathjaxinline]F'=f[/mathjaxinline] is continuous, then  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(b)-F(a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left.\\phantom{\\int } F(x)\\, \\right|_ a^ b.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.199)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      In other words, the definite integral of a function is the difference between the values of its antiderivative at the limits of the definite integral.    We will abbreviate the bordeaux **First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus** as bordeaux **FTC1**.    The FTC1 connects the definite integral to the antiderivative. With this connection, we can now compute definite integrals using antiderivatives, and dispense with Riemann sums.  **The definite integral of any continuous function**  Since the equation in the statement of FTC1 makes sense for general functions, we can use the FTC1 to extend the royalblue **definition of the definite integral** to functions that are not necessarily non-negative. That is,   For any continuous function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] with an antiderivative [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline],  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, \\, \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(b)-F(a)\\qquad (\\text {for any continuous}\\, \\, \\, f).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.200)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      It turns out that to be consistent with FTC1, the Riemann sum formula for definite integrals does not need to change. Consequently, the royalblue **geometric definition** of [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] that is consistent with FTC1 is as follows.  ![ ](/static/images/ftc1_signedarea.svg)   [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(x) \\, dx\\, =\\, \\text {Area above} \\, x\\text {-axis and below }\\, y=f(x)\\, -\\, \\text {Area below} \\, x\\text {-axis and above }\\, y=f(x)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where the areas considered are between the vertical lines [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x=b[/mathjaxinline]. The important point is that the area above the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-axis is counted with a positive sign and the area below the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-axis is counted with a negative sign. In other words, the definite integral of a general function is the bordeaux **signed area bounded by the curve [mathjaxinline]y=f(x)[/mathjaxinline]**.    We will continue to use FTC1, not Riemann sums, to evaluate definite integrals. We will also often use the area interpretation to deduce properties of definite integrals, for example when looking for symmetry.  **Velocity and speed, displacement and distance travelled**  Suppose you are travelling between time [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and time [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline], and your velocity is given by [mathjaxinline]v(t)[/mathjaxinline] and your position by [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] at time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].    Recall that royalblue **Speed** is [mathjaxinline]|v(t)|[/mathjaxinline], the absolute value of the velocity function.    Then,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} v(t) \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(b)-x(a) \\qquad (\\text {Displacement}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.201)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      That is, the integral of the velocity function is the (net) change of position between time [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline], also called the royalblue **displacement**.    On the other hand, [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, \\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} \\left|v(t)\\right| \\, \\, dt\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] gives the royalblue **total distance travelled** between time [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline].  In the case when [mathjaxinline]v(t)>0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]|v(t)|=v(t)[/mathjaxinline], and therefore [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, \\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} v(t) \\, dt \\, \\, =\\, \\, \\int _{a}^{b} \\left|v(t)\\right| \\, \\, dt.\\, \\, \\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] In other words, when you are always travelling in the same direction, then speed is equal to velocity, and total distance traveled is equal to displacement.  **Properties of definite integrals**  Here are some properties of definite integrals. We have discussed and used most of these properties for [mathjaxinline]f>0[/mathjaxinline]. The properties below are true for definite integrals for functions which can be negative as well.  Sums:      [mathjax]\\int _{a}^{b}\\left( f(x) +g(x) \\right) \\, dx \\, =\\, \\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx +\\int _{a}^{b} g(x) \\, dx[/mathjax]|    ---|---   Constant Multiples:      [mathjax]\\int _{a}^{b} c \\, f(x) \\, dx \\, =\\, c\\, \\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx\\qquad \\text {for any constant}\\, c[/mathjax]|    ---|---   Same Upper and Lower Limits:      [mathjax]\\int _{a}^{a} \\, f(x) \\, dx\\, =\\, 0[/mathjax]|    ---|---   Reversing Limits of Integrals:      [mathjax]\\int _{b}^{a} \\, f(x) \\, dx\\, =\\, - \\int _{a}^{b} \\, f(x) \\, dx\\qquad \\text {for any}\\, a,b[/mathjax]|    ---|---      This is the definition of a definite integral with its lower limit greater than its upper limit. It is defined this way to be consistent with FTC1.  Combining integrals:      [mathjax]\\int _{a}^{c} \\, f(x) \\, dx\\, =\\, \\int _{a}^{b} \\, f(x) \\, dx\\, +\\, \\int _{b}^{c} \\, f(x) \\, dx\\qquad \\text {for any}\\, a,b,c[/mathjax]|    ---|---      We have seen this property in the last section with [mathjaxinline]a<b<c[/mathjaxinline]. With the property above on reversing the limits of a definite integral, we can now use this property with [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline],[mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline],[mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] in any order.  **Estimation**  If [mathjaxinline]\\, f(x)\\leq g(x)[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]\\, a\\leq b,\\,[/mathjaxinline] then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx\\, \\, \\, \\leq \\, \\, \\, \\int _{a}^{b} g(x)\\, dx \\qquad (\\text {for}\\, \\, a\\leq b).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Notice that the order of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] matters for this inequality. If instead of [mathjaxinline]a\\leq b[/mathjaxinline] we have [mathjaxinline]b\\leq a[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx\\, \\geq \\, \\int _{a}^{b} g(x)\\, dx \\qquad (b\\leq a).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In other words, if the limits of the integrals are reversed, the inequality is also reversed.  **Change of variables for definite integrals**  When we make a change of variables of an integral in order to evaluate it, we are using the method of substitution. The method of substitution for definite integrals is exactly analogous to the method of substitution for indefinite integrals, except we now need to pay attention to the limits of the integrals.  If  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx = \\int _{a}^{b} g(u(x)) u'(x) \\, dx,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline] does not change sign between [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx = \\int _{a}^{b} g(u(x)) u'(x) \\, dx = \\int _{u(a)}^{u(b)} g(u) \\, du.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      That is, the limits of the integral over [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] are the values of [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] corresponding to the limits of the integral over [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline].  **Caution**  When we use the method of substitution, we need to be very careful about when [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline] (or [mathjaxinline]du[/mathjaxinline]) changes sign. If [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline] changes sign within the integration interval [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], the method of substitution may give the wrong answer. In this case, we need to first rewrite the integral as a sum of two integrals such that within the limits of each integral [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline] does not change sign, and then use the method of substitution on each integral separately.     **Comparing FTC1 and MVT**  If [mathjaxinline]F(x)[/mathjaxinline] is differentiable and [mathjaxinline]F'(x)[/mathjaxinline] is continuous on [mathjaxinline]\\, [a,b][/mathjaxinline]. And let  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Delta F[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(b)-F(a)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.202)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Delta x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b-a.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.203)      Then, the MVT states that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{\\Delta F}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F'(c) \\qquad \\text {for some}\\, c,\\, \\, a<c<b.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.204)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      On the other hand, the FTC1 gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{\\Delta F}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{b-a} \\int _ a^ b F'(x) \\, dx.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.205)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      We see that the FTC1 gives a specific value for [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\Delta F}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline], the average rate of change of [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] over [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], but the MVT does not, since it does not tell us where [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] is.    Therefore, the First Fundamental Theorem much more useful than the Mean Value Theorem. Once we have FTC1 at our disposal, we do not need to use MVT anymore. Nonetheless, the Mean Value Theorem is important as the basis of calculus. We needed it to establish the fact that two antiderivatives of the same function can only differ by a constant. We will need this fact again in order to prove FTC1 in the next section.    Summary", "filename": "theory2-tab23-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 12, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory1-tab17", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/defint_summary.pdf)   **Geometric definition of the definite integral**  The bordeaux **definite integral of [mathjaxinline]f\\,[/mathjaxinline] from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline]** , denoted by  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is the area of the region above the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-axis, below the curve [mathjaxinline]y=f(x)[/mathjaxinline], and in between the two vertical lines [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x=b[/mathjaxinline], as shown shaded in the figure below.  ![A function y equals f of x is plotted in the first quadrant. The points a and b are indicated on the x axis. The region beneath the function and between the vertical lines x equals a and x equals b is shaded.](/static/images/defint_riemann4.svg)  The [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-values [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] are called the bordeaux **lower** and bordeaux **upper limits of the integral**. (This is a different sense of the word \u201climit\" from when we take the limit of a function.)    The only difference between the notation for definite and indefinite integrals is that definite integrals have limits but indefinite integrals do not.     **Summation notation**  The [mathjaxinline]\\sum[/mathjaxinline] notation in a compact way to denote a sum in which each term is obtained from a formula:    [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\sum _{i=1}^ n a_ i = a_1+a_2+\\cdots +a_{n-1}+a_{n}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] indexes the terms, and [mathjaxinline]a_ i[/mathjaxinline] is a formula for the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] term of the sum.   The notation [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sum _{i=1}^ n a_ i[/mathjaxinline] reads \u201cthe sum of [mathjaxinline]a_ i[/mathjaxinline] from [mathjaxinline]i=1[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]i=n[/mathjaxinline].\"    For example, if [mathjaxinline]a_ i=i^2[/mathjaxinline], that is, the formula for the term indexed by [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]i^2[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\sum _{i=1}^ n i^2 = 1^2+2^2+3^2+\\cdots +(n-1)^2+n^2[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Riemann sums**  Let us summarize in precise terms the steps for evaluating [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] using a Riemann Sum.      1. Divide [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline] into [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] equal subintervals.   ![ ](/static/images/defint_nintervals2.svg)  Then each interval is of length  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\Delta x= \\frac{b-a}{n}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Let the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] subinterval be the **base** of [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] rectangle.    2. Choose a point [mathjaxinline]c_ i[/mathjaxinline] within the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] subinterval.Choose [mathjaxinline]f(c_ i)[/mathjaxinline] be the **height** of the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] rectangle.    ![ ](/static/images/defint_ci2.svg)    3. Add up the areas of the [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] rectangles. The total area of [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] rectangles is:   [mathjax]\\underbrace{f(c_1)}_\\text {height}\\, \\underbrace{\\Delta x}_\\text {base} +\\underbrace{f(c_2)}_\\text {height} \\, \\underbrace{\\Delta x}_\\text {base}+\\cdots + \\underbrace{f(c_ n)}_\\text {height} \\underbrace{\\Delta x}_\\text {base} \\ =\\ \\sum _{i=1}^{n} f(c_ i) \\Delta x[/mathjax]|   ---|---     4. Take the limit as the rectangles become infinitesimally thin, ([mathjaxinline]\\Delta x \\rightarrow 0[/mathjaxinline], or equivalent [mathjaxinline]n\\rightarrow \\infty[/mathjaxinline]). This limit is the actual area under the curve between [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline].   [mathjax]\\lim _{n\\rightarrow \\infty }\\, \\sum _{i=1}^{n} \\, f(c_ i) \\Delta x\\ =\\ \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjax]|   ---|---    The sum of the areas of the [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] rectangles, [mathjaxinline]\\sum _{i=1}^{n} f(c_ i) \\Delta x[/mathjaxinline], is called a royalblue **Riemann Sum**. If we pick [mathjaxinline]c_ i[/mathjaxinline] to be the left endpoint of the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] subinterval, the Riemann sum is called a royalblue **left Riemann Sum**. Similarly, if [mathjaxinline]c_ i[/mathjaxinline] is the right endpoint of the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] interval, the Riemann sum is called a royalblue **right Riemann sum**.    However, in the limit [mathjaxinline]n\\rightarrow \\infty[/mathjaxinline] (so that [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x\\rightarrow 0[/mathjaxinline]), this distinction is no longer needed. The limit of any Riemann Sum, no matter what the [mathjaxinline]c_ i[/mathjaxinline]'s within the subinterval are, is equal to the exact area under the curve.    **Cumulative sums**  We have been defining the definite integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] geometrically as the area under a curve. But [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] can represent quantities other than length.  For instance, if [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] represents time, with units of [mathjaxinline]\\text {hours}[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] represents velocity, with units of [mathjaxinline]\\text {km/hour}[/mathjaxinline]. So the units of the integral, [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline], is [mathjaxinline]\\text {km}[/mathjaxinline], which are the units of distance. But the integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] still represents the area under the curve, so the units of this area are [mathjaxinline]\\text {km}[/mathjaxinline].    Most applications of the integral will involve seeing it as a cumulative sum. You will see numerous examples in Unit 3.  Summary", "filename": "theory1-tab17-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 13, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@technique3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@technique3-tab13", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/partialfractions_summary.pdf)  # Summary   **Rational functions**  royalblue **Polynomials** are functions [mathjaxinline]P(x) = a_ n x^ n + a_{n-1}x^{n-1} + \\dotsb + a_1 x + a_0[/mathjaxinline] where the constants [mathjaxinline]a_ i[/mathjaxinline] are real numbers and the powers [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] are non-negative, finite integers.  The royalblue **degree** of a polynomial [mathjaxinline]P(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the integer [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{deg}(P)=n[/mathjaxinline] of the highest order [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] term in the polynomial [mathjaxinline]P(x)[/mathjaxinline].  royalblue **Rational functions** are ratios of polynomials. For example, if [mathjaxinline]P(x)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]Q(x)[/mathjaxinline] are polynomials, then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is a rational function.  **Method of partial fractions**  Given a rational function [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}[/mathjaxinline]  **Step**|  **Example**   ---|---   Given a rational function [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{4x-1}{x^2+x-2}[/mathjaxinline]   (1) Factor the denominator [mathjaxinline]Q(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]Q(x) = x^2+x-2 = (x-1)(x+2)[/mathjaxinline]   (2) Set-up |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{4x-1}{(x-1)(x+2)} = \\frac{A}{x-1}+\\frac{B}{x+2}[/mathjaxinline]   (3) Solve for [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]B[/mathjaxinline] |  Multiply by [mathjaxinline](x-1)[/mathjaxinline]:   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{4x-1}{x+2} = A + \\frac{B}{x+2}(x-1)[/mathjaxinline]   |  Plug in [mathjaxinline]x=1[/mathjaxinline]: (Take the limits as [mathjaxinline]x \\rightarrow 1[/mathjaxinline].)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{4-1}{1+2} = A[/mathjaxinline]   |  Multiply by [mathjaxinline](x+2)[/mathjaxinline]:   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{4x-1}{x-1} = \\frac{A}{x-1}(x+2) +B[/mathjaxinline]   |  Plug in [mathjaxinline]x=-2[/mathjaxinline]: (Take the limits as [mathjaxinline]x \\rightarrow -2[/mathjaxinline].)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{-8-1}{-2-1} = B[/mathjaxinline]   (4) Rewrite rational function. |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{4x-1}{x^2+x-2} = \\frac{1}{x-1}+\\frac{3}{x+2}[/mathjaxinline]      **Cover-up method**  Given a rational function [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]Q(x)[/mathjaxinline] can be factored linearly with distinct factors, and the degree of [mathjaxinline]P(x)[/mathjaxinline] is less than the degree of [mathjaxinline]Q(x)[/mathjaxinline], then the fastest way to apply the method of partial fractions is the following:    1. Factor [mathjaxinline]Q(x)[/mathjaxinline]     2. Set-up     3. Cover-up   **Repeated linear factors**  Given [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{deg}P < \\mathrm{deg}Q[/mathjaxinline]. If [mathjaxinline]Q(x) = (x-a)^ n[/mathjaxinline], then the set-up for partial fractions is as follows:  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)} = \\frac{A_1}{(x-a)} + \\frac{A_2}{(x-a)^2} + \\frac{A_3}{(x-a)^3} + \\dotsb + \\frac{A_ n}{(x-a)^ n}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Quadratic factors in the denominator**  Note that all polynomials with real coefficients can be factors into a product of linear and quadratic factors, where the quadratic factors cannot be factored further.  **Method of partial fractions**|  **Example**   ---|---   (1) Factor denominator [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{x^2}{(x-1)(x^2+1)}[/mathjaxinline]   (2) Setup |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{x^2}{(x-1)(x^2+1)} = \\frac{A}{x-1} + \\frac{Bx+C}{x^2+1}[/mathjaxinline]   (3) Solve for [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]B[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline]. | Cover-up [mathjaxinline]x-1[/mathjaxinline] to find [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline]:   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{1^1+1} = \\frac12 = A[/mathjaxinline]   |  Clear denominator:   |  [mathjaxinline]x^2 = (1/2)(x^2+1) + (Bx+C)(x-1) = (1/2 + B)x^2 + (C-B)x+(1/2-C)[/mathjaxinline]   |  Solve system for [mathjaxinline]B[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline] looking at the coefficients of [mathjaxinline]x^2[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x^0[/mathjaxinline]   |  [mathjaxinline]1 = 1/2 + B \\quad \\Longrightarrow \\quad B = 1/2[/mathjaxinline]   |  [mathjaxinline]0 = 1/2 - C \\quad \\Longrightarrow \\quad C = 1/2[/mathjaxinline]      **Improper fractions**  To integrate a rational function [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{deg}P \\geq \\mathrm{deg}Q[/mathjaxinline]:    1. Use Long division to divide [mathjaxinline]Q(x)[/mathjaxinline] into [mathjaxinline]P(x)[/mathjaxinline] to obtain   [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)} = p(x) + \\frac{r(x)}{Q(x)},[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]p(x)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]r(x)[/mathjaxinline] are polynomials, and [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{deg}r < \\mathrm{deg}Q[/mathjaxinline].    2. Use the method of partial fractions to divide [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{r(x)}{Q(x)}[/mathjaxinline] into simpler pieces to integrate.   Summary", "filename": "technique3-tab13-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 18, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_2-tab21", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/antider2_summary.pdf)   **Differential notation**  Let [mathjaxinline]y= F(x)[/mathjaxinline], the royalblue **differential of y** is defined as  [mathjax]\\displaystyle dy \\, = \\, F'(x) dx.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This is also called the royalblue **differential of F** and denoted royalblue **[mathjaxinline]dF[/mathjaxinline]**.    Rearranging this equation, we get the the Leibniz notation for the derivative, which says the derivative is the ratio of the two differentials [mathjaxinline]dy[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline].    [mathjax]\\displaystyle F'(x)= \\frac{dy}{dx} \\qquad \\left(\\text {or} \\, \\, \\frac{ dF}{dx}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We may think of the differential of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline], as a \"little bit\" of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], and the differential of [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]dy[/mathjaxinline], as a \"little bit\" of [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]. Here, what we mean by a \"little bit\" is really an infinitely small bit, we call these infinitely small quantities \u201cinfinitesimals.\" The point is that even though both [mathjaxinline]dy[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline] are infinitely small, their ratio is NOT. Their ratio is the derivative [mathjaxinline]\\ F'(x)[/mathjaxinline]. In other words, the differential notation says that [mathjaxinline]dy[/mathjaxinline] is proportional to [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline] with constant of proportionality [mathjaxinline]\\ F'(x)[/mathjaxinline] even though both [mathjaxinline]dy[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline] are infinitely small. We use the differential notation as a tool to keep track of how much [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] changes when [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] changes by a tiny tiny tiny [mathjaxinline]\\, \\ldots \\,[/mathjaxinline] tiny bit.    The geometric picture for the differential is the same as that for linear approximation.  ![The graph y equals F of x is shown in the first quadrant of the x y plane. Two points are indicated on the horizontal axis by x and x plus d x. The tangent line at x is shown in pink and extends to x plus delta x. The horizontal component of this line has length d x. The vertical component has height d y which is equal to F prime of x times d x.](/static/images/antider2_Differential.svg)  Let us compare the differential notation with the formula for linear approximations.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text {Linear approximation at }\\, x[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Delta F[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F'(x) \\, \\Delta x,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, \\Delta x \\, \\text {is a finite change in x.}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {Differential notation: }[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle dF[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F'(x)\\, dx,[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, dx \\, \\text {is a tiny tiny }\\ldots \\text {tiny bit of} \\, \\, x[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Antiderivatives**  royalblue **An antiderivative** of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is any function [mathjaxinline]\\ F(x)[/mathjaxinline] such that  [mathjax]\\displaystyle F'(x)\\, = f(x).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Indefinite integral**  Given a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline], the royalblue **indefinite integral** or royalblue **the antiderivative** of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is denoted [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int f(x) dx[/mathjaxinline]. It is the family of functions  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int f(x) \\, dx \\, = F(x) + C[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where [mathjaxinline]\\ F(x)[/mathjaxinline] is any antiderivative of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]\\, C[/mathjaxinline] is any constant.    We call [mathjaxinline]\\int[/mathjaxinline] the royalblue **integral sign** ,[mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] the royalblue **integrand** , and [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline] the royalblue **constant of integration**.    The constant of integration is present in this definition because the derivative of a function determines only the shape of the function, but the derivative does not change if the function is shifted up or down by the same constant everywhere.    **Uniqueness of the indefinite integral**  The indefinite integral  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int f(x) \\, dx \\, = F(x) + C[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is termed \u201cindefinite\" since it contains an undetermined constant [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline] and is not just one function but a family of infinitely many functions, parameterized by [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline].    On the other hand, the constant is the only ambiguity of the indefinite integral due to the MVT, which guarantees that any two antiderivatives of the same function can differ only by a constant.     **Integrals of powers**  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int \\, x^ p\\ dx \\, \\, = \\qquad \\begin{cases} \\displaystyle \\frac{x^{p+1}}{p+1} & \\mbox{if } p \\neq -1 \\\\\\ \\ln \\left(|x|\\right) & \\mbox{if } p = -1. \\end{cases}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **First rules of Integration**  |  Integration Rules |  Differentiation Rules   ---|---|---   Constant multiple: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int k \\, f (x) \\, dx \\, = \\, \\ k \\int \\, f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline]|  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle d(kF)\\, =\\, k \\, dF[/mathjaxinline]   Sum: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int \\left( f(x)+g(x) \\right)\\, dx =\\ \\int f(x)\\, dx +\\int g(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline]|  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle d(F+G)\\, =\\, dF+dG[/mathjaxinline]      On the other hand, the following naive product and quotient rules do NOT work.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int f\\cdot g dx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textbf{DOES NOT EQUAL}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ \\left( \\int \\, f dx\\right)\\cdot \\left(\\int \\, g dx\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int \\frac{f}{g} \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textbf{DOES NOT EQUAL}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{ \\int f \\, dx }{ \\int g\\, dx}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Method of substitution**  The method of substitution is the integration analogue of the chain rule.    If  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle g(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(u(x))\\, u'(x) \\, dx,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---      that is, the differential [mathjaxinline]g(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] is the result of a chain rule, then  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int g(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int f(u(x))\\, u'(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int f(u) \\, du[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(u(x))+C[/mathjaxinline] |  |      where [mathjaxinline]\\ F(u)[/mathjaxinline] is an antiderivative of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(u)[/mathjaxinline].    Summary", "filename": "antider_2-tab21-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 21, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory3-tab18", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/ftc2_summary.pdf)   **The Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus**  The bordeaux **Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus** states the following.   Given a continuous function [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline], if  [mathjax]\\displaystyle G(x)=\\int _{a}^{x} f(t)\\, dt \\qquad (\\, \\, t\\, \\, \\text {between}\\, \\, a\\, \\, \\text {and}\\, x),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      then  [mathjax]G'(x)=f(x).[/mathjax]|   ---|---   ![Go to text below image](/static/images/ftc2_G.svg)   Geometrically, [mathjaxinline]G(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the area between [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]. This area varies as [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] varies.        We will abbreviate this theorem by bordeaux **FTC2**.    In terms of differential equations, FTC2 says that [mathjaxinline]G(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the solution to the following differential equation and initial condition:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y'[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {differential equation})[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.318)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {initial condition}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.319)      The initial condition [mathjaxinline]y(a)=0[/mathjaxinline] is satisfied because [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, \\displaystyle G(a)=\\int _{a}^{a} f(t)\\, dt = 0[/mathjaxinline].    Recall that any function [mathjaxinline]G[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]G'=f[/mathjaxinline] is an antiderivative of [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline]. Hence, FTC2 gives us a formula for an antiderivative of [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline]. This formula is different from the formulas you have seen. It is in terms of a definite integral, and is called an royalblue **integral formula**.  **Note:** The integrand [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] can be any continuous function, not just the ones whose antiderivative we know how to find. These integral formulas are still useful there are numerical methods that allow us to compute them.   **FTC2 and the chain rule**  For any continuous function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline], and differentiable function [mathjaxinline]u(x)[/mathjaxinline],    |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}\\int _{a}^{u(x)} f(t)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(u(x))u'(x).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.320)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      This is because  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{u(x)} f(t)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle G(u(x))[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {where}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle G(y)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{y} f(t)\\, dt.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.321)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      In other words, the integral [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, \\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{u(x)} f(t)\\, dt\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] can be written as a composition of the two functions [mathjaxinline]G[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline]. We can then apply the chain rule and FTC2 to get the derivative.   **The two fundamental theorems of calculus**  Here is another point of view of the two fundamental theorems of calculus together. This is what we mentioned in the introductory (very first) video of this section.    FTC1:        Given a differentiable function [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] with continuous derivative [mathjaxinline]F'[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{x}F'(t) \\, dt \\, =\\, F(x)-F(a),[/mathjax]|   ---|---   FTC2:        Given a continuous function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}\\int _{a}^{x} f(t) \\, dt = f(x),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In other words, FTC1 says that if we start with a function [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline], and first differentiate and then integrate (from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]), we will get back the function [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] up to a constant, which is given by [mathjaxinline]F(a)[/mathjaxinline].    On the other hand, FTC2 says that if we start with a function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline], and first integrate (from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]) and then differentiate, we will get back to [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline]. Notice there is no ambiguity of a constant here.    So, the two fundamental theorems together say that differentiation and integration (from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]) are \u201cinverse\" operations of one another, up to a constant.   **Constructing functions using integrals**  Recall the FTC2 gives the integral formula  [mathjax]\\displaystyle G(x) = \\int _{a}^{x} f(t) \\, dt[/mathjax]|   ---|---      as the solution to the following differential equation and initial condition:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y'[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {differential equation})[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.322)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {initial condition}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.323)      Depending on what the differential equation is, [mathjaxinline]G(x)[/mathjaxinline] can be a function we already know, or one that cannot be expressed (without an integral) in terms of any function we already know. There are many functions of either kind.  For example, the logarithmic function can be defined using an integral:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle L(x)\\,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, \\int _{1}^{x} \\frac{dt}{t}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ln (x) \\qquad \\text {where}\\, \\, x>0.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.324)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      On the other hand, the integral of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, e^{-t^2},\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] the royalblue **bell curve** , is a function defined by an integral and cannot be expressed in terms of functions we already know:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle F(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\int _{0}^{x} e^{-t^2} \\, dt.[/mathjaxinline] | | (2.325)   ---|---|---|---|---      This function is central in probability and will be discussed more in the next unit.    Finally, even though we may not have explicit formulas for the functions defined by integral formulas, we can apply FTC2 to find their derivatives. Therefore, we have all of our usual tools at our disposal. For example, we can graph them, or approximate them by linear and quadratic approximations.     **Summary of the logarithm**  We have now seen the exponential and the logarithmic functions in two different ways. Let us summarize.    In _Calculus 1A_ , we defined the exponential function [mathjaxinline]E(y)[/mathjaxinline] to be the solution to the differential equation and initial condition:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle E'(y)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle E(y)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {differential equation})[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.326)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle E(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {initial condition} ).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.327)      We then let[mathjaxinline]\\, e=E(1)\\,[/mathjaxinline] and denoted [mathjaxinline]\\, E(y)[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, e^ y[/mathjaxinline].    We defined the logarithm as the inverse of [mathjaxinline]E(y)[/mathjaxinline]  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {Definition of the logarithm}:[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ln (x)\\, \\, =\\, \\, E^{-1}(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.328)   ---|---|---|---|---      The properties of the logarithm were derived from the properties of the exponential.  Product: |  [mathjaxinline]e^ a\\cdot e^ b\\, \\, =\\, \\, e^{a+b}[/mathjaxinline]| [mathjaxinline]\\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline]|  [mathjaxinline]\\ln (A\\cdot B)\\, \\, =\\, \\, \\ln (A)+ \\ln (B)[/mathjaxinline],   ---|---|---|---   Reciprocal:|  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{e^ a}\\, \\, =\\, \\, e^{-a}[/mathjaxinline]|  [mathjaxinline]\\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline]| [mathjaxinline]\\ln \\left(\\frac{1}{A}\\right)\\, \\, =\\, \\, -\\ln (A)[/mathjaxinline].      On the other hand, in this section, we first define the logarithm to be the solution to the differential equation and initial condition below:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle L'(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{x}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {differential equation})[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.329)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle L(1)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {initial condition} ).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.330)      The FTC2 gives the integral formula for [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text {Definition of the logarithm}:[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle L(x)\\, \\, =\\, \\, \\int _{1}^{x}\\, \\frac{dt}{t}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.331)   ---|---|---|---|---      We then define [mathjaxinline]e[/mathjaxinline] to be the number such that [mathjaxinline]L(e)=1[/mathjaxinline], and the exponential function to be the inverse of [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {Definition of the exponential}:[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^ y\\, \\, =\\, \\, L^{-1}(y).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.332)   ---|---|---|---|---      To derive the properties of logarithm, we perform different changes of variable to the integral formula [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, \\displaystyle L(x)= \\int _{1}^{x}\\, \\frac{dt}{t}.[/mathjaxinline]  Summary", "filename": "theory3-tab18-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

So while the shaded region is bounded by an arc of arc length [mathjaxinline]2\\theta[/mathjaxinline], the area of the shaded region is [mathjaxinline]\\theta[/mathjaxinline].  ### Geometric description of hyperbolic trig functions  The point labeled in the image, [mathjaxinline](\\cosh (t), \\sinh (t) ),[/mathjaxinline] is defined to be the point on the hyperbola [mathjaxinline]x^2 - y^2 =1[/mathjaxinline] such that the area of the shaded region is [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].  ![Half of a hyperbola is plotted in the first and fourth quadrants of the x y plane. FTC1:        Given a differentiable function [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] with continuous derivative [mathjaxinline]F'[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\left.\\int _{a}^{b }F'(t) \\, dt \\, =\\, F(x)\\, \\, \\right|_ a^ b.[/mathjax]|   ---|---   FTC2:        Given a continuous function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}\\int _{a}^{x} f(t) \\, dt = f(x).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We will now prove FTC2 and then FTC1. {"pageid": 25, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory1-tab6", "text": "**Main idea**  In general, the region under a curve is not a simple shape whose area we have a formula for. In this case, we will start with an approximation of the area and then take the limit as the approximation approaches the actual area. We will do this in the following three steps.    1. Divide the region under the curve into \u201cstrips\", as shown in the figure below.   ![A function y equals f of x is plotted in the first quadrant. The vertical lines x equals a and x equals b are indicated by dashed lines. Three additional dashed lines that start at the x axis and extend upwards to the function height are indicated by dashed lines between x equals a and x equals b.](/static/images/defint_riemann1decreasing.svg)  Approximate the area of each strip by the area of a rectangle.  ![A function y equals f of x is plotted in the first quadrant. The vertical lines x equals a and x equals b are indicated by dashed lines. Four rectangles are fitted between x equals a and and x equals b where the height of each rectangle is approximately the height of the function f of x.](/static/images/defint_riemann2decreasing.svg)    2. Add up the areas of all the rectangles.     3. Take the limit as the rectangles become infinitesimally thin.   The main idea is that as the rectangles become thinner and thinner, the difference between the area covered by the rectangles and the area under the curve becomes smaller and smaller. And in the limit when the rectangles are infinitesimally small, these become exactly equal.  Main idea", "filename": "theory1-tab6-text2.html", "title": "Main idea"}

{"pageid": 27, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory3-tab15", "text": "**The integral of the bell curve: summary**  The integral of the bell curve is an example of a function that cannot be expressed (without using an integral) in terms of functions that we already know.    Recall that the royalblue **bell curve** is the graph of [mathjaxinline]e^{-t^2}[/mathjaxinline]. As above, let  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle F(x)= \\int _{0}^{x} e^{-t^2}\\, dt.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.299)   ---|---|---|---   ![Go to text below image](/static/images/ftc2_bell.svg)   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(x) = \\int _{0}^{x} e^{-t^2} \\, dt = \\text {Area of shaded region.}.[/mathjaxinline]       Using the first and second derivatives of [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline], we sketched the graph of [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] as shown below.    ![Go to text below image](/static/images/ftc2_bellintegral.svg)   Graph of [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(x)[/mathjaxinline]    **Properties**  Here are two properties of [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline].      * [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] is odd: [mathjaxinline]F(-x)\\, =\\, - F(x)[/mathjaxinline]      * [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lim _{x\\rightarrow \\infty } F(x)= \\frac{\\sqrt{\\pi }}{2}[/mathjaxinline];[mathjaxinline]\\, \\, \\displaystyle \\lim _{x\\rightarrow -\\infty } F(x)= \\frac{-\\sqrt{\\pi }}{2}[/mathjaxinline].   ![Go to text below image](/static/images/ftc2_bellinfinite.svg)   Geometrically, [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lim _{x\\rightarrow \\infty } F(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the area of the shaded infinite stretch.     The graph of [mathjaxinline]F(x)[/mathjaxinline] has two horizontal asymptotes at [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y=\\frac{\\sqrt{\\pi }}{2}[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y=-\\frac{\\sqrt{\\pi }}{2}[/mathjaxinline].  ![Go to text above image](/static/images/ftc2_bellintegraly.svg)       **The error function**  The bordeaux **error function** , denoted by [mathjaxinline]\\, \\text {erf}(x)[/mathjaxinline], is the renormalized version of [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(x) = \\int _{0}^{x} e^{-t^2} \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] that has horizontal asymptotes at [mathjaxinline]y=\\pm 1[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text {erf}(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{2}{\\sqrt{\\pi }}\\, F(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{2}{\\sqrt{\\pi }}\\, \\int _{0}^{x} e^{-t^2}\\, dt\\qquad (\\text {Error function}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.300)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      The error function is a new transcendental function to add to your repertoire of functions along with [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, e^ x[/mathjaxinline],[mathjaxinline]\\, \\, \\ln (x)[/mathjaxinline], and trigonometric functions.  The integral of the bell curve", "filename": "theory3-tab15-text1.html", "title": "The integral of the bell curve"}

{"pageid": 28, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory2-tab3", "text": "**The First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus**  The bordeaux **First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus** states that:   If [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] is differentiable, and [mathjaxinline]F'=f[/mathjaxinline] is continuous, then  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(b)-F(a)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.89)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      In other words, the definite integral of a function is the difference between the values of its antiderivative at the limits of the definite integral.    We will abbreviate the bordeaux **First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus** as bordeaux **FTC1**.    The FTC1 connects the definite integral to the antiderivative. With this connection, we can now compute definite integrals using antiderivatives, and dispense with Riemann sums.  Notice that in the first problem, you have checked that this statement is true when [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is equal to a constant, [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline].    The FTC1", "filename": "theory2-tab3-text1.html", "title": "The FTC1"}

{"pageid": 29, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications1-tab17", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/areasvolumes_summary.pdf)   **Process for finding areas and volumes**    1. Draw a picture     2. Identify limits of integration     3. Identify integrand     4. Integrate to solve (as needed)   **Volumes by slicing**  The volume of a slice of bread is  [mathjaxinline]dV = A(x)\\, dx,[/mathjaxinline]  where [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline] is the width of the slice, and [mathjaxinline]A(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the cross-sectional area. The volume of the entire loaf is  [mathjaxinline]V = \\int A(x) \\, dx.[/mathjaxinline]  **Method of disks**  ![2d rectangle area element](/static/images/methoddisks2d.svg) ![2d disk, volume element](/static/images/methoddisks3d.svg)  The method of disks gives the differential volume element for a curve rotated about the [mathjaxinline]x-[/mathjaxinline] axis  [mathjax]dV = \\pi y^2\\, dx.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Method of shells**  ![](/static/images/methodshells.svg)  The method of shells for a curve [mathjaxinline]y=f(x)[/mathjaxinline] rotated about the [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]-axis:  [mathjax]dV = 2\\pi x y\\, dx.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Method of washers**  ![](/static/images/app1_washer2.svg)  The volume of an infinitesimal washer is given by  [mathjax]dV = \\pi (y_{\\textrm{outer}}^2 - y_{\\textrm{inner}}^2)\\, dx.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Summary", "filename": "applications1-tab17-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 30, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@technique1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@technique1-tab8", "text": "**Integral with two even positive exponents**  To evaluate  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int \\sin ^{2m}(x) \\cos ^{2n}(x) \\, dx \\, \\, \\qquad 2m,2n\\geq 0 \\, \\, \\text {even integers},[/mathjaxinline] | | (4.85)   ---|---|---|---      we apply the half angle formulas to the integrand as many times as needed, until the integrand does not contain any non-constant term in which both exponents of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\sin \\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\cos \\,[/mathjaxinline] are even, but instead may contain terms with odd powers of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\sin (2kx)\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, \\cos (2lx)\\,[/mathjaxinline] where [mathjaxinline]\\, 2k\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, 2l\\,[/mathjaxinline] are even integers. {"pageid": 32, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications4-tab6", "text": "To approximate the integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline]:    * Subdivide the interval into [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] pieces ([mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] must be even) [mathjaxinline]a = x_0 < x_1 < \\dotsb < x_{n-1} < x_ n = b[/mathjaxinline].     * Let [mathjaxinline]y_0 = f(x_0)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]y_1 = f(x_1)[/mathjaxinline], ... , [mathjaxinline]y_{n-1}= f(x_{n-1})[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]y_ n = f(x_ n)[/mathjaxinline].     * [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x = \\displaystyle \\frac{b-a}{n}[/mathjaxinline].     * **Simpson's Rule** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx \\approx \\frac{\\Delta x}{3} \\left( y_0 + 4y_1 + 2y_2 + 4 y_3 + \\dotsb +2y_{n-2} + 4y_{n-1} + y_ n \\right)[/mathjaxinline]   Simpson's Rule", "filename": "applications4-tab6-text1.html", "title": "Simpson's Rule"}

{"pageid": 34, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications2-tab3", "text": "When we talk about the royalblue **average** in this course, we mean the royalblue **mean** , which is the sum of all values divided by the number of values. {"pageid": 37, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_1-tab10", "text": "Recall that a function [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is **increasing** if whenever [mathjaxinline]a < b[/mathjaxinline], we have [mathjaxinline]f(a) \\leq f(b)[/mathjaxinline].   Similarly, a function [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is **decreasing** if whenever [mathjaxinline]a < b[/mathjaxinline], we have [mathjaxinline]f(a) \\geq f(b)[/mathjaxinline].  The conclusions we just made using the MVT on all subintervals of [mathjaxinline][A,B][/mathjaxinline] are fundamental facts we have been relying on:    * If [mathjaxinline]x'(t) \\geq 0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline](A,B)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is **increasing or staying the same** over [mathjaxinline][A,B][/mathjaxinline].     * If [mathjaxinline]x'(t) \\leq 0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline](A,B)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is **decreasing or staying the same** over [mathjaxinline][A,B][/mathjaxinline].     * If [mathjaxinline]x'(t)=0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline](A,B)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is **constant** over [mathjaxinline][A,B][/mathjaxinline].   And the MVT gives the following consequences with strict inequalities as well:    * If [mathjaxinline]x'(t) >0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline](A,B)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is **strictly increasing** over [mathjaxinline][A,B][/mathjaxinline].     * If [mathjaxinline]x'(t) <0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline](A,B)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is **strictly decreasing** over [mathjaxinline][A,B][/mathjaxinline].   These facts need proofs and their proofs are based on the MVT as seen in the exercises you have done. The subtlety is that the MVT relates the infinitesimal behavior of the function, the derivative, which is defined at each point, with the macroscopic behavior, the total change over an interval.  Old News", "filename": "antider_1-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Old News"}

{"pageid": 39, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications2-tab12", "text": "royalblue **Work** is done on an object when royalblue **energy** is transferred to that object.  In the cauldron example, heat energy was transferred to the water in the cauldron. We were able to measure the work done, or the energy transferred, by measuring the total change in temperature.  royalblue **Work** , royalblue **heat** , and royalblue **energy** have the same units, but we typically measure them differently.    * We measure royalblue **work** in Newton-meters (N[mathjaxinline]\\cdot[/mathjaxinline]m).     * We measure royalblue **heat** in calories (cal).     * And we measure royalblue **energy** in Joules (J).   James Joule recognized and measured the relationship between heat energy and mechanical work.  [mathjax]\\displaystyle 1 \\text { cal} =4.186 \\text { J} = 4.186 \\text { N}\\cdot \\text {m}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The approach to solving problems involving work, heat, or energy is the same, and involves computing an integral.  A common example of mechanical work is when a force is applied over a distance. This force applied to the object transfers energy in the form of kinetic or potential energy. In this case, the formula for work is given by  [mathjax]\\displaystyle W = \\int F \\, dx.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In the next problems, you will be asked to use integral computations to compute work by thinking of the integral as a cumulative sum. Hint: think about units!  Rather than use the Newton-meter, we will be using the English units of foot- pounds (ft[mathjaxinline]\\cdot[/mathjaxinline]lbf) for students who have not seen the Newton before. Here, [mathjaxinline]\\, 1 \\text {lbf}[/mathjaxinline] is a unit of force and equals the weight of a 1 pound mass: [mathjaxinline]\\, 1 \\, \\text {lbf}\\, = 1\\text {lb}\\cdot 9.8 \\text {m}/\\text {s}^2.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Below is the conversion between the two systems of units:  [mathjax]\\displaystyle 1 \\text {ft}\\cdot \\text {lbf} \\, = \\, 1 \\text {ft}\\cdot \\text {lb}\\cdot 9.8 \\frac{\\text {m}}{\\text {s}^2} \\cdot \\frac{1\\text { kg}}{2.20462\\text { lb}} \\cdot \\frac{1\\text { m}}{3.28084\\text { ft}} \\, =\\, 1.35 \\frac{\\text {kg}\\cdot \\text {m}^2}{\\text {s}^2} \\, =\\, 1.35 \\text { N}\\cdot \\text {m}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Work and energy", "filename": "applications2-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Work and energy"}

{"pageid": 41, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory3-tab8", "text": "We will now review the proof from the video.    Recall the statement of FTC1:   Given a differentiable function [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] with continuous derivative [mathjaxinline]F'=f[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(x) \\, dx \\, =\\, F(b)- F(a).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      First, define  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle G(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{x} f(t)\\, dt.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.263)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Note that [mathjaxinline]G(x)[/mathjaxinline] makes sense as the limit of Riemann sums.  Second, since [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] is continuous, the FTC2 says that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle G'=f.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.264)   ---|---|---|---      Now, since [mathjaxinline]F'=f[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]G'=f[/mathjaxinline], both [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]G[/mathjaxinline] are antiderivatives of [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore, as a consequence of the Mean Value Theorem,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F'(x)\\, =\\, G'(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Rightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(x)\\, =\\, G(x)+C[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.265)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      where [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline] is a constant.    Finally, we compute [mathjaxinline]F(b)-F(a)[/mathjaxinline] in terms of [mathjaxinline]G[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle F(b)-F(a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (G(b)+C)\\, -\\, (G(a)+C)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.266)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle G(b)-G(a)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.267)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(t)\\, dt- \\int _{a}^{a} f(t)\\, dt\\qquad (\\text {Definition of}\\, \\, G)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.268)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(t)\\, dt - 0[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.269)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(t)\\, dt.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.270)      Therefore,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(t)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =F(b)-F(a).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.271)   ---|---|---|---|---      This is the statement of FTC1, even though the integration variable is renamed [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline].  Proof of FTC1", "filename": "theory3-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Proof of FTC1"}

{"pageid": 44, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_2-tab7", "text": "royalblue **An antiderivative** of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is any function [mathjaxinline]\\ F(x)[/mathjaxinline] such that  [mathjax]\\displaystyle F'(x)\\, = f(x).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In other words, an antiderivative of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is another function whose derivative is [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 46, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@technique3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@technique3-tab8", "text": "Note that all polynomials with real coefficients can be factored into a product of linear and quadratic factors, where the quadratic factors cannot be factored further.  **Method of partial fractions**|  **Example**   ---|---   (1) Factor denominator [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{x^2}{(x-1)(x^2+1)}[/mathjaxinline]   (2) Setup |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{x^2}{(x-1)(x^2+1)} = \\frac{A}{x-1} + \\frac{Bx+C}{x^2+1}[/mathjaxinline]   (3) Solve for [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]B[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline]. | Cover-up [mathjaxinline]x-1[/mathjaxinline] to find [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline]:   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{1^2+1} = \\frac12 = A[/mathjaxinline]   |  Clear denominator:   |  [mathjaxinline]x^2 = (1/2)(x^2+1) + (Bx+C)(x-1) = (1/2 + B)x^2 + (C-B)x+(1/2-C)[/mathjaxinline]   |  Solve system for [mathjaxinline]B[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline] looking at the coefficients of [mathjaxinline]x^2[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x^0[/mathjaxinline]   |  [mathjaxinline]1 = 1/2 + B \\quad \\Longrightarrow \\quad B = 1/2[/mathjaxinline]   |  [mathjaxinline]0 = 1/2 - C \\quad \\Longrightarrow \\quad C = 1/2[/mathjaxinline]  Quadratic factor in denominator", "filename": "technique3-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Quadratic factor in denominator"}

{"pageid": 54, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@technique2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@technique2-tab11", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/trigsub_summary.pdf)   **Summary of trig substitutions**   **If integrand contains:**|  **Make substitution:**|  **To get:**   ---|---|---   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sqrt{a^2-x^2}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x = \\begin{cases} a\\cos (\\theta )\\\\\\ a\\sin (\\theta )\\end{cases}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sqrt{a^2-x^2}= \\begin{cases} a\\sin (\\theta ) \\\\\\ \\displaystyle a\\cos \\theta )\\end{cases}[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sqrt{a^2+x^2}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x = a\\tan (\\theta )[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sqrt{a^2+x^2}= a\\sec (\\theta )[/mathjaxinline]   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sqrt{x^2-a^2}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x = a\\sec (\\theta )[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sqrt{x^2-a^2}=a\\tan (\\theta )[/mathjaxinline]      **Completing the square**  We use completing the square to rewrite any quadratic function into a form which is more conducive to using trigonometric substitution.  To complete the square means to rewrite any quadratic function [mathjaxinline]\\, Ax^2+Bx+C\\,[/mathjaxinline] into the form [mathjaxinline]\\, A(x+b)^2+c[/mathjaxinline].  Here is the algebra:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle Ax^2+Bx+C[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A\\left(x^2+\\frac{B}{A}x \\right)+C \\qquad \\text {Factor out }\\, A[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.372)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {Add and subtract the square term}\\qquad[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A\\left(x^2+\\frac{B}{A}x+ \\left(\\frac{B}{2A} \\right)^2 \\right) - A\\left(\\frac{B}{2A} \\right)^2+C[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.373)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A\\left(x+\\frac{B}{2A} \\right)^2 +\\left(-\\frac{B^2}{4A}+C\\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.374)       **Worked example with trig substitution**   **Step**|  **Example**   ---|---   (1) Consider the integral: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int \\frac{dx}{x^2\\sqrt{1+x^2}}[/mathjaxinline]   (2) Identify ugliest part of integral: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sqrt{1+x^2}[/mathjaxinline]   (3) |  Make a substitution to simplify ugly expression:   ---   Based on [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sec ^2\\theta = 1+\\tan ^2\\theta[/mathjaxinline].   [mathjaxinline]\\begin{cases} x= \\tan \\theta \\\\\\ \\sqrt{1+x^2} = \\sqrt{\\sec ^2\\theta } = \\sec \\theta \\\\\\ dx = \\sec ^2\\theta \\, d\\theta \\end{cases}[/mathjaxinline]   (4) Plug into integral: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int \\frac{dx}{x^2\\sqrt{1+x^2}} = \\int \\frac{\\sec \\theta \\, d\\theta }{\\tan ^2 \\theta }[/mathjaxinline]   (5) Rewrite in terms of [mathjaxinline]\\sin[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\cos[/mathjaxinline]: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\int \\frac{\\cos \\theta \\, d\\theta }{\\sin ^2 \\theta }[/mathjaxinline]   (6) Still not done. Need to evaluate this integral. |   How about trying a direct substitution? |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{cases} u & =& \\sin \\theta \\Longrightarrow u^2 = \\sin ^2 \\theta \\\\\\ du & = & \\cos \\theta \\, d\\theta \\\\\\ \\end{cases}[/mathjaxinline]   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\int \\frac{du}{u^2}[/mathjaxinline]   (7) Evaluate the integral. |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{-1}{u}+C[/mathjaxinline]   This is the end of the calculus. |   (8) The rest is back substitution. |   First replace [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]\\sin \\theta[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]= \\displaystyle \\frac{-1}{\\sin \\theta } +C[/mathjaxinline]   (9) Draw a diagram of [mathjaxinline]x =\\tan \\theta[/mathjaxinline]: | ![Right triangle with one acute angle labeled theta. The side opposite theta is labeled x and the side adjacent to theta is labeled 1.](/static/images/trigsub_tri1.svg)   (10) Use diagram to determine [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\sin \\theta }[/mathjaxinline] in terms of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]: | ![Right triangle with one acute angle labeled theta. The side opposite theta is labeled x and the side adjacent to theta is labeled 1. The hypotenuse is labeled square root of 1 plus x squared.](/static/images/trigsub_tri2.svg)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\sin \\theta } = \\frac{\\sqrt{1+x^2}}{x}[/mathjaxinline]   (11) Rewrite in terms of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]: |  [mathjaxinline]= \\displaystyle -\\frac{\\sqrt{1+x^2}}{x} + C[/mathjaxinline]      **Undoing trig substitution**  To undo a trig substitution, you must often evaluate a function of the form a trig function of an inverse trig function. For example:    * [mathjaxinline]\\csc \\left(\\arctan x \\right)[/mathjaxinline]     * [mathjaxinline]\\tan \\left(\\mathrm{arccsc} x\\right)[/mathjaxinline]   To do this the steps are as follows:  **Undoing a trig substitution**|  **Worked example**   ---|---   (1) Compute the composite: |  [mathjaxinline]\\tan \\underbrace{\\left( \\mathrm{arccsc}(x)\\right)}_{\\theta }[/mathjaxinline].   (2) Draw a picture of |   [mathjaxinline]\\begin{array}{ll}& \\theta = \\mathrm{arccsc}(x) \\\\\\ \\Longleftrightarrow & \\csc \\theta = x\\\\\\ \\Longleftrightarrow & \\displaystyle \\sin \\theta = \\frac{1}{x} \\end{array}[/mathjaxinline] | ![Right triangle with one acute angle labeled theta. The side opposite theta is labeled 1 and the hypotenuse is labeled x.](/static/images/trigsub_tri0.svg)   (3) Find length of remaining side: | ![Right triangle with one acute angle labeled theta. The side opposite theta is labeled 1 and the hypotenuse is labeled x. The side adjacent to theta is labeled square root of x squared minus 1.](/static/images/trigsub_tri0b.svg)   (4) Compute trig function: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\tan \\theta = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{x^2-1}}[/mathjaxinline]      From the pictures and formulas, we can see that we used [mathjaxinline]1 < x < \\infty[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]0 < \\theta < \\pi /2[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 57, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory3-tab6", "text": "We have evaluated in the video an example of the following.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}\\int _{a}^{u(x)} f(t)\\, dt.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.228)   ---|---|---|---      (In the video, [mathjaxinline]u(x)=\\sin (x)[/mathjaxinline].) In general, we can evaluate this using the following procedure.   Let  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle G(u)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\int _{a}^{u} f(t)\\, dt,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.229)   ---|---|---|---|---      then  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle G(u(x))[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\int _{a}^{u(x)} f(t)\\, dt.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.230)   ---|---|---|---|---      That is, decompose the definite integral with [mathjaxinline]u(x)[/mathjaxinline] as its upper limit as the composition of the two functions [mathjaxinline]G(u)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]u(x)[/mathjaxinline]. Now, let us apply the chain rule to find its derivative.    |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx} G(u(x))[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle G'(u(x)) \\cdot u'(x)\\qquad (\\text {chain rule});[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.231)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {or equivalently}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dG}{dx}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left.\\frac{dG}{du}\\right|_{u=u(x)} \\cdot \\frac{du}{dx},[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.232)      where [mathjaxinline]G'(u(x))[/mathjaxinline] is the derivative of [mathjaxinline]G[/mathjaxinline] with respect to [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] evaluated at [mathjaxinline]u(x)[/mathjaxinline]. Another notation for [mathjaxinline]G'(u(x))[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left.\\frac{dG}{du}\\right|_{u=u(x)}[/mathjaxinline]. By FTC2,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle G'(u)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = f(u)\\qquad (\\text {FTC2}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.233)   ---|---|---|---|---      Therefore,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}G(u(x))[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(u(x)) \\cdot u'(x),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.234)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx} \\int _{a}^{u(x)} f(t)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(u(x)) \\cdot u'(x).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.235)  FTC2 and the chain rule", "filename": "theory3-tab6-text1.html", "title": "FTC2 and the chain rule"}
