{"pageid": 61, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory2-tab22", "text": "Let us compare what the First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus and what the Mean Value Theorem say about the average rate of change of a function.    If [mathjaxinline]F(x)[/mathjaxinline] is differentiable and [mathjaxinline]F'(x)[/mathjaxinline] is continuous on [mathjaxinline]\\, [a,b][/mathjaxinline]. And let  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Delta F[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(b)-F(a)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.195)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Delta x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle b-a.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.196)      Then, the MVT states that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{\\Delta F}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F'(c) \\qquad \\text {for some}\\, c,\\, \\, a<c<b.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.197)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      On the other hand, the FTC1 gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{\\Delta F}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{b-a} \\int _ a^ b F'(x) \\, dx.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.198)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      We see that the FTC1 gives a specific value for [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\Delta F}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline], the average rate of change of [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] over [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], but the MVT does not, since it does not tell us where [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] is.    Therefore, the First Fundamental Theorem is much more useful than the Mean Value Theorem. Once we have FTC1 at our disposal, we do not need to use MVT anymore. Nonetheless, the Mean Value Theorem is important as the basis of calculus. We needed it to establish the fact that two antiderivatives of the same function can only differ by a constant. {"pageid": 63, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory1-tab16", "text": "**Cumulative sums**  We have been defining definite integrals geometrically as the area under a curve. But [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] can represent quantities other than length.  For instance, in the previous problem, [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] represents time, with units of [mathjaxinline]\\text {hours}[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]f(t)[/mathjaxinline] represents velocity, with units of [mathjaxinline]\\text {km/hour}[/mathjaxinline]. So the units of the integral, [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(t)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline], is [mathjaxinline]\\text {km}[/mathjaxinline], which are the units of distance. But the integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(t)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] still represents the area under the curve, so the units of this area are [mathjaxinline]\\text {km}[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 64, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications4-tab2", "text": "### Objectives    * Use royalblue **Riemann sums** , the royalblue **Midpoint Rule** , the royalblue **Trapezoidal Rule** , and royalblue **Simpson's Rule** to approximate integrals.     * Recognize royalblue **numerical methods** as weighted averages.     * Derive Simpson's Rule.     * Use royalblue **error bounds** of these methods to understand the accuracy of your approximations.   ### Contents: 11 pages  9 videos (34 minutes at 1x speed) 12 problems  Objectives", "filename": "applications4-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 65, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory3-tab10", "text": "**Constructing functions using integrals**  Recall the FTC2 gives the integral formula  [mathjax]\\displaystyle G(x) = \\int _{a}^{x} f(t) \\, dt,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      as the solution to the following differential equation and initial condition:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y'[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {differential equation})[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.275)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {initial condition}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.276)      Depending on what the differential equation is, [mathjaxinline]G(x)[/mathjaxinline] can be a function we already know. An example is the function we have just seen in the previous problem.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle L(x)\\,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, \\int _{1}^{x} \\frac{dt}{t}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ln (x) \\qquad (x>0)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.277)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      Notice that while the integrand [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{t}[/mathjaxinline] is a ratio of two polynomials, [mathjaxinline]L(x)[/mathjaxinline] cannot be written in terms of polynomials using algebraic operations [mathjaxinline]+[/mathjaxinline],[mathjaxinline]-[/mathjaxinline],[mathjaxinline]\\cdot[/mathjaxinline],[mathjaxinline]/[/mathjaxinline],[mathjaxinline]\\sqrt[n]{\\phantom{2}}[/mathjaxinline]. It is an example of a \u201ctranscendental\" function, a function that \u201ctranscends\" algebra.    On the other hand, the solution that FTC2 gives for another differential equation may be a function that cannot be expressed (without an integral) in terms of any function we already know. For example,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle F(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\int _{0}^{x} e^{-t^2} \\, dt[/mathjaxinline] | | (2.278)   ---|---|---|---|---      is the solution to  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y'[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{-x^2}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {differential equation})[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.279)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(0)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {initial condition}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.280)   ![Go to text below image](/static/images/ftc2_bell.svg)   Geometrically, [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(x) = \\int _{0}^{x} e^{-t^2} \\, dt = \\text {Area of shaded region}.[/mathjaxinline]        This function is used extensively in probability.    Finally, even though we may not have explicit formulas for these functions defined by integral formulas, we can apply FTC2 to find their derivatives. Therefore, we have all of our usual tools at our disposal. For example, we can graph them, or approximate them by linear and quadratic approximations.    Let us now discuss the two examples above in more detail.    Constructing new functions", "filename": "theory3-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Constructing new functions"}

\\displaystyle \\frac{b-a}{n}[/mathjaxinline].     * **Left Riemann sum** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx \\approx \\Delta x\\left( y_0 + y_1 + \\dotsb + y_{n-1}\\right)[/mathjaxinline]     * **Right Riemann sum** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx \\approx \\Delta x\\left( y_1 + y_2 + \\dotsb + y_ n\\right)[/mathjaxinline]   **Riemann sums: Midpoint Rule**  To approximate the integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline]:    * Subdivide the interval into [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] pieces [mathjaxinline]a = x_0 < x_1 < \\dotsb < x_{n-1} < x_ n = b[/mathjaxinline].     * Find the value of the function on the midpoint of each interval   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\tilde{y}_1 = f\\left(\\frac{x_0+x_1}{2}\\right)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\tilde{y}_2 = f\\left(\\frac{x_1+x_2}{2}\\right)[/mathjaxinline], ... , [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\tilde{y}_{n}= f\\left(\\frac{x_{n-1}+x_ n}{2}\\right)[/mathjaxinline].    * [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x = \\displaystyle \\frac{b-a}{n}[/mathjaxinline].     * **Midpoint Rule** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx \\approx \\Delta x\\left( \\tilde{y}_1 + \\tilde{y}_2 + \\dotsb + \\tilde{y}_{n}\\right)[/mathjaxinline]   **Trapezoidal Rule**  To approximate the integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline]:    * Subdivide the interval into [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] pieces [mathjaxinline]a = x_0 < x_1 < \\dotsb < x_{n-1} < x_ n = b[/mathjaxinline].     * Let y_1 + \\dotsb + y_{n-1} + \\frac12 y_ n \\right).[/mathjaxinline]   **Simpson's Rule**  To approximate the integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline]:    * n)[/mathjaxinline].     * [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x = \\displaystyle \\frac{b-a}{n}[/mathjaxinline].     * **Simpson's Rule** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx \\approx {"pageid": 67, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications3-tab10", "text": "**Food for thought**  Try using a change of variables to find the normalization constant for the normal distribution [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^{-x^2/2\\sigma ^2}.[/mathjaxinline]  #### Normalization constant  We want to find the constant [mathjaxinline]C[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } C e^{-x^2/2\\sigma ^2}\\, dx = 1[/mathjaxinline]. We use change of variables [mathjaxinline]u = x/(\\sqrt{2}\\sigma )[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]du = dx/(\\sqrt{2}\\sigma )[/mathjaxinline] to compute [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } e^{-x^2/2\\sigma ^2}\\, dx[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } e^{-x^2/2\\sigma ^2}\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty }e^{-u^2}\\, (\\sqrt{2}\\sigma )\\, du[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.60)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle 2\\int _{0}^{\\infty }e^{-u^2}\\, (\\sqrt{2}\\sigma )\\, du \\qquad \\text {(even function)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.61)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle 2\\sqrt{2}\\sigma \\cdot \\frac{\\sqrt{\\pi }}{2} = \\sigma \\sqrt{2\\pi }[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.62)      Therefore [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle C = \\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{2\\pi }}.[/mathjaxinline]  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Try computing the expected value of [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{2\\pi }} e^{\\frac{-(x-\\mu )^2}{2\\sigma ^2}}[/mathjaxinline] by hand.  #### Expected value  Let [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u=x-\\mu[/mathjaxinline]. Then [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle du = dx[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } \\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{2\\pi }} x e^{\\frac{-(x-\\mu )^2}{2\\sigma ^2}} \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty }\\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{2\\pi }} (u+\\mu ) e^{-u^2/2\\sigma ^2}\\, du[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.63)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty }\\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{2\\pi }} ue^{-u^2/2\\sigma ^2}\\, du + \\mu \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty }\\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{2\\pi }} e^{-u^2/2\\sigma ^2}\\, du[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.64)      Let's compute each integral separately.  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty }\\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{2\\pi }} ue^{-u^2/2\\sigma ^2}\\, du \\longrightarrow 0,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      because the integrand is an odd function.  The integral  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\mu \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty }\\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{2\\pi }} e^{-u^2/2\\sigma ^2}\\, du = \\mu[/mathjax]|   ---|---      because [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{2\\pi }} e^{-u^2/2\\sigma ^2}[/mathjaxinline] is a probability distribution.  Thus the expected value [mathjaxinline]E=\\mu .[/mathjaxinline]  [Show](javascript: {return false;})  Food for thought", "filename": "applications3-tab10-text2.html", "title": "Food for thought"}

{"pageid": 71, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications4-tab4", "text": "**Riemann sums: Midpoint Rule**  To approximate the integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline], instead of taking the left or right endpoints, we can instead take the midpoint!    * Subdivide the interval into [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] pieces [mathjaxinline]a = x_0 < x_1 < \\dotsb < x_{n-1} < x_ n = b[/mathjaxinline].     * Find the value of the function on the midpoint of each interval   [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\tilde{y}_1 = f\\left(\\frac{x_0+x_1}{2}\\right)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\tilde{y}_2 = f\\left(\\frac{x_1+x_2}{2}\\right)[/mathjaxinline], ... , [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\tilde{y}_{n}= f\\left(\\frac{x_{n-1}+x_ n}{2}\\right)[/mathjaxinline].    * [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x = \\displaystyle \\frac{b-a}{n}[/mathjaxinline].     * **Midpoint Rule** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx \\approx \\Delta x\\left( \\tilde{y}_1 + \\tilde{y}_2 + \\dotsb + \\tilde{y}_{n}\\right)[/mathjaxinline]   Riemann sums: Midpoint Rule", "filename": "applications4-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Riemann sums: Midpoint Rule"}

{"pageid": 72, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory2-tab15", "text": "**Change of variables for definite integrals**  When we make a change of variables of an integral in order to evaluate it, we are using the method of substitution. The method of substitution for definite integrals is exactly analogous to the method of substitution for indefinite integrals, except we now need to pay attention to the limits of the integrals.  If  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx = \\int _{a}^{b} g(u(x)) u'(x) \\, dx,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline] does not change sign between [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline], then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx = \\int _{a}^{b} g(u(x)) u'(x) \\, dx = \\int _{u(a)}^{u(b)} g(u) \\, du.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      That is, the limits of the integral over [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] are the values of [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] corresponding to the limits of the integral over [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline].  Change of Variables", "filename": "theory2-tab15-text1.html", "title": "Change of Variables"}

{"pageid": 73, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications2-tab2", "text": "### Objectives    * Find the royalblue **average value** of a continuous function.     * Interpret the average value royalblue **geometrically**.     * Use integrals to compute royalblue **work**.     * Compute royalblue **weighted averages** of continuous functions.     * Interpret royalblue **center of mass** as the average value of position weighted by mass density.   ### Contents: 13 pages  11 videos (48 minutes at 1x speed) 16 problems  Objectives", "filename": "applications2-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 74, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_4-tab2", "text": "We keep using the word modeling. You may be wondering, what exactly is mathematical modeling?  bordeaux **Modeling** is the process of translating a real world problem into mathematics. The bordeaux **model** is the resulting mathematics.  In order to make the mathematical model, we typically make several simplifying assumptions. Once a model is created, it is tested and changed based on experimental data. The model is used to make predictions, which can be used to validate the model through experiment. The advantage of mathematical models is that it is cheaper and faster to run a simulation than to build an experiment.  This section will show you the process of creating a model for the shape of a hanging cable. This section is at a higher level than the rest of the course content and is **optional**.  Modeling", "filename": "antider_4-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Modeling"}

{"pageid": 75, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@technique3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@technique3-tab4", "text": "Given a rational function [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}[/mathjaxinline]  **Step**|  **Example**   ---|---   Given a rational function [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{P(x)}{Q(x)}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{4x-1}{x^2+x-2}[/mathjaxinline]   (1) Factor the denominator [mathjaxinline]Q(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]Q(x) = x^2+x-2 = (x-1)(x+2)[/mathjaxinline]   (2) Set-up |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{4x-1}{(x-1)(x+2)} = \\frac{A}{x-1}+\\frac{B}{x+2}[/mathjaxinline]   (3) Solve for [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]B[/mathjaxinline] | **For** [mathjaxinline]A[/mathjaxinline]:   |  Multiply by [mathjaxinline](x-1)[/mathjaxinline]:   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{4x-1}{x+2} = A + \\frac{B}{x+2}(x-1)[/mathjaxinline]   |  Plug in [mathjaxinline]x=1[/mathjaxinline]: (Take the limits as [mathjaxinline]x \\rightarrow 1[/mathjaxinline].)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{4-1}{1+2} = A[/mathjaxinline]   | **For** [mathjaxinline]B[/mathjaxinline]:   |  Multiply by [mathjaxinline](x+2)[/mathjaxinline]:   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{4x-1}{x-1} = \\frac{A}{x-1}(x+2) +B[/mathjaxinline]   |  Plug in [mathjaxinline]x=-2[/mathjaxinline]: (Take the limits as [mathjaxinline]x \\rightarrow -2[/mathjaxinline].)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{-8-1}{-2-1} = B[/mathjaxinline]   (4) Rewrite rational function. |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{4x-1}{x^2+x-2} = \\frac{1}{x-1}+\\frac{3}{x+2}[/mathjaxinline]  Partial fractions", "filename": "technique3-tab4-text1.html", "title": "Partial fractions"}

{"pageid": 79, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_3-tab13", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/diffeq_summary.pdf)   **Separation of variables**  A differential equation is bordeaux **separable** if it can be written in the form [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)g(y)[/mathjaxinline].  To solve a separable differential equation, separate all terms involving [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] from terms involving [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline], and anti-differentiate both sides.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dx}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = f(x) g(y)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{g(y)}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = f(x) dx[/mathjaxinline] |  |   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int \\frac{dy}{g(y)}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\int f(x) dx[/mathjaxinline] |  |      **Initial conditions**   **Theorem**  Given a differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)g(y)[/mathjaxinline] and an bordeaux **initial condition** [mathjaxinline]y(a) = b[/mathjaxinline], if [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]g'[/mathjaxinline] are continuous near [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline], then there is a unique function [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] whose derivative is given by [mathjaxinline]f(x)g(y)[/mathjaxinline] and that passes through the point [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline].  **Slope fields**  The bordeaux **slope field** is a diagram that helps us to visualize the information in a first order differential equation. The slope field is obtained as follows. At each point [mathjaxinline](x,y)[/mathjaxinline], you draw a short segment whose slope is the _value_ of [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y'[/mathjaxinline] at the point [mathjaxinline](x,y)[/mathjaxinline]. The solution curves must be tangent to the slope field at all points.  **Euler's method**  Given the differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dx} = x+y[/mathjaxinline]:    1. Choose a step size [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] (The smaller the step size, the more accurate the approximation.)     2. Let [mathjaxinline](x_0, y_0)[/mathjaxinline] be the initial condition.     3. We can use the differential equation and step size to determine the value of the function at [mathjaxinline]x_1=x+h[/mathjaxinline]:   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_{1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_0 + h[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_{1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_0 + (x_0 + y_0)h \\quad \\textrm{linear approximation}[/mathjaxinline] |  |     4. Iterate this process:   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_{k+1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_ k + h[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_{k+1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_ k + (x_ k + y_ k)h \\quad \\textrm{linear approximation}[/mathjaxinline] |  |    Summary", "filename": "antider_3-tab13-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 82, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_1-tab8", "text": "We will be using the notions of upper and lower bounds so we will discuss these here.    A number [mathjaxinline]M[/mathjaxinline] is an royalblue **upper bound** on a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] if  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle[/mathjaxinline] |  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle M[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {for all } \\, \\, x\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      and a number [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] is a royalblue **lower bound** on a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] if  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle m[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  |  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {for all } \\, \\, x\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] | |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      We can consider upper and lower bounds over the entire real number line, or over an interval.  ![A function y equals f of x is plotted in the x y plane. {"pageid": 85, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory3-tab9", "text": "Here is another point of view of the two fundamental theorems of calculus together. This is what we mentioned in the introductory (very first) video of this section. (This video is at the bottom of the page again here.)    FTC1:        Given a differentiable function [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] with continuous derivative [mathjaxinline]F'[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{x}F'(t) \\, dt \\, =\\, F(x)-F(a).[/mathjax]|   ---|---   FTC2:        Given a continuous function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline],  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{d}{dx}\\int _{a}^{x} f(t) \\, dt = f(x).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In other words, FTC1 says that if we start with a function [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline], and first differentiate and then integrate (from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]), we will get back the function [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] up to a constant, which is given by [mathjaxinline]F(a)[/mathjaxinline].    On the other hand, FTC2 says that if we start with a function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline], and first integrate (from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]) and then differentiate, we will get back to [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline]. Notice there is no ambiguity of a constant here.    So, the two fundamental theorems together say that differentiation and integration (from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]) are \u201cinverse\" operations of one another, up to a constant.  Comparing FTC1 and FTC2", "filename": "theory3-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Comparing FTC1 and FTC2"}

{"pageid": 90, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@technique1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@technique1-tab7", "text": "**The half angle formulas**  Recall  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\sin ^2(a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1-\\cos (2a)}{2}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.81)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cos ^2(a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1+\\cos (2a)}{2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.82)  Half angle formulas", "filename": "technique1-tab7-text1.html", "title": "Half angle formulas"}

{"pageid": 91, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_1-tab19", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/mvtintro2_summary.pdf)   **The Mean Value Theorem (MVT)**  If [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is continuous on [mathjaxinline]a\\leq t \\leq b[/mathjaxinline], and differentiable on [mathjaxinline]a<t<b[/mathjaxinline], that is, [mathjaxinline]x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] is defined for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, a<t<b[/mathjaxinline], then    [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{x(b)-x(a)}{b-a} \\, = x'(c) \\qquad \\text {for some }c,\\, \\, \\text {with } a<c<b.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Equivalently, in geometric terms, there is at least one point [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline], with [mathjaxinline]a<c<b[/mathjaxinline], at which the tangent line is parallel to the secant line through [mathjaxinline](a, x(a))[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline](b, x(b))[/mathjaxinline]:  ![An increasing, concave down curve is plotted in the x versus t plane. The points on the horizontal axis are indicated by a, c, and b where a is less c and c is less than b. The tangent line to the graph is drawn at c comma x of c.](/static/images/antider1_xtgraph_MVT_statement.svg)  **Upper and Lower Bounds**  We have introduced the notion of upper and lower bounds.    A number [mathjaxinline]M[/mathjaxinline] is an royalblue **upper bound** of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] if  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle[/mathjaxinline] |  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle M[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {for all } \\, \\, x\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      and a number [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] is a royalblue **lower bound** of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] if  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle m[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  |  | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {for all } \\, \\, x\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] | |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      We can consider upper and lower bounds on the entire real number line, or on an interval.  ![A function y equals f of x is plotted in the x y plane. The function is bounded above by capital M and bounded below by lowercase m. The function's behavior fluctuates, but it never reaches heights above capital M or below lowercase m.](/static/images/antider1_upperbounddef2.svg)[mathjax]\\displaystyle m\\leq f(x)\\leq M[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In other words, an upper bound of a function is a number that is larger than or equal to all values of the function. A lower bound of a function is a number which is smaller than or equal to all values of the function.  **Old news**  We have been relying on the following fundamental facts whenever we try to understand a function using its derivative. But in fact, these facts are consequences of the mean value theorem.      * If [mathjaxinline]x'(t) \\geq 0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline](A,B)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is **increasing or staying the same** over [mathjaxinline][A,B][/mathjaxinline].     * If [mathjaxinline]x'(t) > 0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline](A,B)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is **strictly increasing** over [mathjaxinline][A,B][/mathjaxinline].     * If [mathjaxinline]x'(t) \\leq 0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline](A,B)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is **decreasing or staying the same** over [mathjaxinline][A,B][/mathjaxinline].     * If [mathjaxinline]x'(t) < 0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline](A,B)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is **strictly decreasing** over [mathjaxinline][A,B][/mathjaxinline].     * If [mathjaxinline]x'(t)=0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline](A,B)[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is **constant** over [mathjaxinline][A,B][/mathjaxinline].   These facts need proofs and their proofs are based on the MVT. The subtlety is that the MVT relates the infinitesimal behavior of the function, the derivative, which is defined at a point, to the macroscopic behavior of the function, the total change over an interval.  **Bounding the average rate of change**  The equality in the MVT can be used to restrict the range of possible values of the average rate of change and the total change.    More precisely, if there are numbers [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]M[/mathjaxinline] such that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle m[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x'(c)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle M[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {for all}\\, \\, c\\, \\, \\text {with}\\, \\, a<c<b,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (1.111)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      that is, [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] is a lower bound and [mathjaxinline]M[/mathjaxinline] is an upper bounds on [mathjaxinline]x'(c)[/mathjaxinline] over [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline], then the MVT implies the following.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle m[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{x(b)-x(a)}{b-a}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle M[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {(Bounds on the average rate of change)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (1.112)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m\\, \\cdot \\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(b)-x(a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle M \\, \\cdot \\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {(Bounds on the total change)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (1.113)      In other words, a lower bound on the derivative is also a lower bound on the average rate of change, and an upper bound on the derivative is also an upper bound on the average rate of change. Also, the product of a lower bound on the derivative with the length of an interval, is a lower bound on the total change of the function over that interval. Similarly, the product of an upper bound on the derivative with the length of an interval, is an upper bound on the total change of the function over that interval.    When we know the maximum and minimum values of [mathjaxinline]x'(t)[/mathjaxinline], we can use them as bounds on [mathjaxinline]x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] and obtain the following.    |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\min _{a \\leq t \\leq b} x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{x(b)-x(a)}{b-a}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\max _{a\\leq t \\leq b} x'(t).[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {(Bounds on the average rate of change)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (1.114)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\min _{a \\leq t \\leq b} x'(t) \\, \\cdot \\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(b)-x(a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\max _{a\\leq t \\leq b} x'(t) \\, \\cdot \\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {(Bounds on the total change)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (1.115)      In other words, the average rate of change must be in between the maximum and the minimum of the derivative, and the total change must be in between the maximum and minimum of the derivative multiplied by the length of the interval.    Summary", "filename": "antider_1-tab19-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 92, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications2-tab13", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/averagevalue_summary.pdf)   **Average value of f(x)**  The average value of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] on an interval [mathjaxinline]a \\leq x \\leq b[/mathjaxinline] is given by  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{b-a}\\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Average value and average rate of change**  Fundamental Theorem of calculus tells us that the average rate of change of [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] over [mathjaxinline]a \\leq t \\leq b[/mathjaxinline] is the **same** as the average value of [mathjaxinline]y'[/mathjaxinline] over [mathjaxinline]a \\leq t \\leq b[/mathjaxinline].  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\text {ave}(y') = \\frac{1}{b-a}\\int _ a^ b y'(t)\\, dt = \\frac{y(b)-y(a)}{b-a} = \\text {average rate of change of} y(t).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Weighted average**  The royalblue **weighted average** value of a function [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline], weighted by a weight function [mathjaxinline]\\, w(x)[/mathjaxinline] on an interval [mathjaxinline]a \\leq x \\leq b[/mathjaxinline] is given by  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{\\int _ a^ b f(x)w(x)\\, dx}{\\int _ a^ b w(x)\\, dx}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Center of mass**  ### [mathjaxinline]1-[/mathjaxinline]dimensional  For a 1-dimensional rod of length [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] with linear density function [mathjaxinline]\\lambda (x)[/mathjaxinline] (measured in mass per unit length), the center of mass is the weighted average:  [mathjax]\\displaystyle x_ c = \\frac{\\int _0^ L x \\lambda (x)\\, dx}{\\int _0^ L \\lambda (x)\\, dx}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ### [mathjaxinline]2-[/mathjaxinline]dimensional  For a 2-dimensional region whose mass is proportional to area, the center of mass, or centroid [mathjaxinline](\\bar{x}, \\bar{y})[/mathjaxinline], is the weighted average of the position with respect to the area. The [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]- and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]- coordinates of the centroid are computed by the following integrals:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\bar{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{\\int _ a^ b x \\, dA}{\\int _ a^ b dA}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.22)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\bar{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{\\int _ a^ b y\\, dA}{\\int _ a^ b dA},[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.23)      where [mathjaxinline]dA[/mathjaxinline] is the infinitesimal area, and we must define the limits of integration so that we integrate over the entire region with respect to [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] respectively.  **Work, heat, and energy**  royalblue **Work** is done on an object when royalblue **energy** is transferred to that object.  royalblue **Work** , royalblue **heat** , and royalblue **energy** have the same units, but we typically measure them differently.    * We measure royalblue **work** in Newton-meters (N[mathjaxinline]\\cdot[/mathjaxinline]m).     * We measure royalblue **heat** in calories (cal).     * And we measure royalblue **energy** in Joules (J).   James Joule recognized and measured the relationship between heat energy and mechanical work.  [mathjax]\\displaystyle 1 \\text {cal} =4.186 \\text { J} = 4.186 \\text { N}\\cdot \\text {m}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The approach to solving problems involving work, heat, or energy is the same, and involves computing an integral.  A common example of mechanical work is when a force is applied over a distance. This force applied to the object transfers energy in the form of kinetic or potential energy. In this case, the formula for work is given by  [mathjax]\\displaystyle W = \\int F \\, dx.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In the cauldron example, heat energy was transferred to the water in the cauldron. We measured the work done, or the energy transferred, by measuring the total change in temperature [mathjaxinline]T[/mathjaxinline]:  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int T dV.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Summary", "filename": "applications2-tab13-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 93, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_3-tab8", "text": "### Theorem  Given a differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)g(y)[/mathjaxinline] and an bordeaux **initial condition** [mathjaxinline]y(a) = b[/mathjaxinline], if [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]g[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]g'[/mathjaxinline] are continuous near [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline], then there is a unique function [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] whose derivative is given by [mathjaxinline]f(x)g(y)[/mathjaxinline] and that passes through the point [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline].  Initial conditions", "filename": "antider_3-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Initial conditions"}

{"pageid": 94, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications4-tab9", "text": "**Error bounds**  ### Error bound of Trapezoidal Rule  Suppose [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left| f^{\\prime \\prime }(x) \\right| \\leq M[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]a \\leq x \\leq b[/mathjaxinline]. Then the error of the Trapezoidal Rule over [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] subintervals is given by  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\left| E_ T \\right| \\leq \\frac{M(b-a)^3}{12n^2}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ### Error bound of Midpoint Rule  Suppose [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left| f^{\\prime \\prime }(x) \\right| \\leq M[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]a \\leq x \\leq b[/mathjaxinline]. Then the error of the Midpoint Rule over [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] subintervals is given by  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\left| E_ M \\right| \\leq \\frac{M(b-a)^3}{24n^2}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      ### Error bound of Simpson's Rule  Suppose [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\left| f^{(4)}(x) \\right| \\leq M[/mathjaxinline] for [mathjaxinline]a \\leq x \\leq b[/mathjaxinline]. Then the error of the Simpson's Rule over [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] subintervals is given by  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\left| E_ S \\right| \\leq \\frac{M(b-a)^5}{180n^4}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Error bounds", "filename": "applications4-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Error bounds"}

{"pageid": 99, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_3-tab11", "text": "Congratulations! You just carried out the first two steps of Euler's Method. We can repeat this process to come up with an iterative formula for the value of the function on successive intervals.  Given the differential equation [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{dy}{dx} = x+y[/mathjaxinline]:    1. Choose a step size [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] (The smaller the step size, the more accurate the approximation.)     2. Let [mathjaxinline](x_0, y_0)[/mathjaxinline] be the initial condition.     3. We can use the differential equation and step size to determine the value of the function at [mathjaxinline]x_1=x+h[/mathjaxinline]:   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_{1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = x_0 + h[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_{1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = y_0 + (x_0 + y_0)h \\quad \\textrm{linear approximation}[/mathjaxinline] |  |     4. Iterate this process:   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_{k+1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = x_ k + h[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y_{k+1}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = y_ k + (x_ k + y_ k)h \\quad \\textrm{linear approximation}[/mathjaxinline] |  |    Once we have an iterative formula, this is something that we can program into a computer! The following python script is the process a computer uses to apply Euler's method for as many steps, and with as small a step size as you want.                #set initial condition     x,y = x0, y0          #set step size     h=0.1          #count iterations of method     stepcounter = 0          #determine how many steps to take     while stepcounter < 1000:        y= y+(x+y)*h        x+=h        stepcounter+= 1       The smaller the step [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline], the better the approximation. You can visualize Euler's method by using the mathlet below. Use the dropdown menu to choose a differential equation, choose a step size, and click on the graph to select an initial value. Watch as the process unfolds! See what happens for different values of [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline].  Error  Euler's Method", "filename": "antider_3-tab11-text1.html", "title": "Euler's Method"}

{"pageid": 102, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@prep-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@prep-tab3", "text": "These two problems from old AP exams are particularly nice at tying multiple concepts together. We will not offer solutions to these AP problems. Instead we encourage you to try the problems on your own, and discuss solutions on the forum.  ### 2011 AP BC Free Response Question #4:  The graph of a differentiable function [mathjaxinline]y=f(x)[/mathjaxinline] with domain [mathjaxinline]0 \\leq x \\leq 10[/mathjaxinline] is shown in the figure below.  ![](/static/images/exam2prep_AP.svg)    * The area of the region enclosed between the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-axis for [mathjaxinline]0 \\leq x \\leq 5[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]10[/mathjaxinline].     * The area of the region enclosed between the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] and the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-axis for [mathjaxinline]5 \\leq x \\leq 10[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]27[/mathjaxinline].     * The arc length of the portion of the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] between [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x=5[/mathjaxinline] is 11.     * The arc length of the portion of the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] between [mathjaxinline]x=5[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x=10[/mathjaxinline] is 18.     * The function [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] has exactly two critical points located at [mathjaxinline]x=3[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x=8[/mathjaxinline].   (a) Find the average value of [mathjaxinline]\\ f[/mathjaxinline] on the interval [mathjaxinline]0 \\leq f \\leq 5[/mathjaxinline].  (b) Evaluate [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _0^{10}\\left(3f(x)+2\\right)\\, dx.[/mathjaxinline]  (c) Let [mathjaxinline]\\ g(x) = \\displaystyle \\int _5^ x f(t) \\, dt[/mathjaxinline]. On what intervals, if any, is the graph of [mathjaxinline]\\ g[/mathjaxinline] both concave up and decreasing?  (d) The function [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] is defined by [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ h(x) = 2f\\left(\\frac{x}{2}\\right)[/mathjaxinline]. The derivative of [mathjaxinline]h[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]h'(x) = f'\\left(\\frac{x}{2}\\right)[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 103, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_2-tab3", "text": "**Differential notation**  (In the following, we have used [mathjaxinline]\\ F(x)[/mathjaxinline] in place of [mathjaxinline]\\ f(x)[/mathjaxinline] in the video to match with the notation we use later on, but the content remains the same as in the video.)    Let [mathjaxinline]y= F(x)[/mathjaxinline], the royalblue **differential of y** is defined as  [mathjax]\\displaystyle dy \\, = \\, F'(x) dx.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This is also called the royalblue **differential of F** and denoted royalblue **[mathjaxinline]dF[/mathjaxinline]**.    Rearranging this equation, we get the the Leibniz notation for the derivative, which says the derivative is the ratio of the two differentials [mathjaxinline]dy[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline].    [mathjax]\\displaystyle F'(x)= \\frac{dy}{dx} \\qquad \\left(\\text {or} \\, \\, \\frac{ dF}{dx}\\right)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We may think of the differential of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline], as a \"little bit\" of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline], and the differential of [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]dy[/mathjaxinline], as a \"little bit\" of [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]. Here, what we mean by a \"little bit\" is really an infinitely small bit, we call these infinitely small quantities \u201cinfinitesimals.\" The point is that even though both [mathjaxinline]dy[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline] are infinitely small, their ratio is NOT. Their ratio is the derivative [mathjaxinline]\\ F'(x)[/mathjaxinline]. In other words, the differential notation says that [mathjaxinline]dy[/mathjaxinline] is proportional to [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline] with constant of proportionality [mathjaxinline]\\ F'(x)[/mathjaxinline] even though both [mathjaxinline]dy[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]dx[/mathjaxinline] are infinitely small. We use the differential notation as a tool to keep track of how much [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] changes when [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] changes by a tiny tiny tiny [mathjaxinline]\\, \\ldots \\,[/mathjaxinline] tiny bit.    The geometric picture for the differential is the same as that for linear approximation.  ![The graph y equals F of x is shown in the first quadrant of the x y plane. Two points are indicated on the horizontal axis by x and x plus d x. The tangent line at x is shown in pink and extends to x plus delta x. The horizontal component of this line has length d x. The vertical component has height d y which is equal to F prime of x times d x.](/static/images/antider2_Differential.svg)  Let us compare the differential notation with the formula for linear approximations.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text {Linear approximation at }\\, x[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Delta F[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F'(x) \\, \\Delta x,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, \\Delta x \\, \\text {is a finite change in x.}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {Differential notation: }[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle dF[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F'(x)\\, dx,[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, dx \\, \\text {is a tiny tiny }\\ldots \\text {tiny bit of} \\, \\, x[/mathjaxinline] |  |      This notation will appear in the definition of the integral and in the rest of this course.  Differential notation", "filename": "antider_2-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Differential notation"}

{"pageid": 104, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory2-tab3", "text": "**Notation**  Here is a new notation for denoting the difference of the values of a function at two points.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\left.\\phantom{\\int }F(x)\\, \\right|_ a^ b[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(b)-F(a)[/mathjaxinline] | | (2.90)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Notice the order of the difference. This is the function evaluated at [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline], written at the top of the vertical bar, minus the function evaluated at [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline], at the bottom of the vertical bar.  Difference Notation", "filename": "theory2-tab3-text2.html", "title": "Difference Notation"}

{"pageid": 105, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory3-tab3", "text": "**The Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus**  The bordeaux **Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus** states the following.   Given a continuous function [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline]. If  [mathjax]\\displaystyle G(x)=\\int _{a}^{x} f(t)\\, dt \\qquad (\\, \\, t\\, \\, \\text {between}\\, \\, a\\, \\, \\text {and}\\, x),[/mathjax]|   ---|---      then  [mathjax]G'(x)=f(x).[/mathjax]|   ---|---   ![See caption](/static/images/ftc2_G.svg)   Geometrically, [mathjaxinline]G(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the area under the curve [mathjaxinline]y=f(t)[/mathjaxinline] between [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]. This area varies as [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] varies.        We will abbreviate this theorem by bordeaux **FTC2**.    In terms of differential equations, FTC2 says that [mathjaxinline]G(x)[/mathjaxinline] is the solution to the following differential equation and initial condition:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y'[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {differential equation})[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.211)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle y(a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 0[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle (\\text {initial condition}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.212)      The initial condition [mathjaxinline]y(a)=0[/mathjaxinline] is satisfied because [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, \\displaystyle G(a)=\\int _{a}^{a} f(t)\\, dt = 0[/mathjaxinline].    Recall that any function [mathjaxinline]G[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]G'=f[/mathjaxinline] is an antiderivative of [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline]. Hence, FTC2 gives us a formula for an antiderivative of [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline]. This formula is different from the formulas you have seen. It is in terms of a definite integral, and is called an royalblue **integral formula**.  **Note:** The integrand [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] can be any continuous function, not just the ones whose antiderivative we know how to find. These integral formulas are still useful because there are numerical methods that allow us to compute them.  You have just verified FTC2 for a constant function [mathjaxinline]f(x)=m[/mathjaxinline] in the previous problem.    The FTC2", "filename": "theory3-tab3-text1.html", "title": "The FTC2"}

{"pageid": 106, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@technique4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@technique4-tab10", "text": "Let us look at an example in which the original integral reappears on the right hand side of the formula after applying integration by parts.    Use integration by parts to evaluate [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\int e^ x \\cos (x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline].    |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =e^ x;[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v'[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\cos (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.527)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u'[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =e^ x;[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\sin (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.528)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int \\underbrace{e^ x}_ u \\, \\, \\underbrace{\\cos (x)}_{v'}\\, dx\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\quad \\underbrace{e^ x}_{u}\\, \\, \\underbrace{\\sin (x)}_{v} - \\int \\underbrace{\\sin (x)}_{v}\\, \\, \\underbrace{e^ x}_{u'}\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.529)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = e^ x\\sin (x) - \\, \\int e^ x\\, \\sin (x)\\, dx.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.530)      Next, we integrate by parts again to try to evaluate the resulting integral [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\int e^ x\\, \\sin (x)\\, dx\\,[/mathjaxinline]:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle u[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =e^ x;[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v'[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\sin (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.531)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u'[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =e^ x;[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =-\\cos (x)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.532)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int \\underbrace{e^ x}_ u \\, \\, \\underbrace{\\sin (x)}_{v'}\\, dx\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\quad \\underbrace{e^ x}_{u}\\, \\, \\underbrace{\\left(-\\cos (x)\\right)}_{v} - \\int \\underbrace{\\left(-\\cos (x)\\right)}_{v}\\, \\, \\underbrace{e^ x}_{u'}\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.533)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = -e^ x\\cos (x) + \\, \\int e^ x\\, \\cos (x)\\, dx.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.534)      Therefore, combining the above, we get :  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int e^ x \\, \\cos (x)\\, dx\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^ x\\sin (x) \\, - \\, \\int e^ x\\, \\sin (x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.535)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^ x\\sin (x)\\, -\\, \\left(-e^ x\\cos (x) + \\, \\int e^ x\\, \\cos (x)\\, dx\\, \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.536)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^ x\\, \\left(\\sin (x)\\, +\\, \\cos (x)\\right) - \\, \\int e^ x\\, \\cos (x)\\, dx.\\,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.537)      The integral we started with [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\int e^ x\\, \\cos (x)\\, dx\\,[/mathjaxinline] appears again on the right hand side of our formula! It looks like we have just gone around in circles, but actually we are almost done, because the unknown integral appears with coefficient [mathjaxinline]+1[/mathjaxinline] on the left hand side and [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline] on the right hand side, and we so can solve for it by adding it to both sides:    |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int e^ x \\, \\cos (x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^ x\\, \\left(\\sin (x)\\, +\\, \\cos (x)\\right) - \\, \\int e^ x\\, \\cos (x)\\, dx.\\,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.538)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 2\\, \\left( \\int e^ x \\, \\cos (x)\\, dx \\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle e^ x\\, \\left(\\sin (x)\\, +\\, \\cos (x)\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.539)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int e^ x\\, \\cos (x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{e^ x \\left(\\sin (x)+\\cos (x)\\right)}{2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.540)      The final answer is [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int e^ x\\, \\cos (x)\\, dx = \\frac{e^ x \\left(\\sin (x)+\\cos (x)\\right)}{2} + C.[/mathjaxinline]  Original integral reappears", "filename": "technique4-tab10-text1.html", "title": "Original integral reappears"}

{"pageid": 110, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@logistics-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@logistics-tab5", "text": "There are 4 categories of graded problems in 18.01.2x: in-lecture Exercises, Part A Homework, Part B Homework, and the Final Exam.    * **Exercises** These are the problems that are interspersed between videos in each lecture. These problems count for 20% of your grade   These problems will be used to motivate theory, practice a concept you just learned, and review material from previous sequences that we are using. While you are graded on these problems, they are low-stakes: you have multiple attempts, and have the opportunity to look at the answer after you have submitted a correct answer or run out of attempts. This is where you will do the majority of your learning. We encourage you to make mistakes and learn from them!    * **Part A Homework** Each unit has 1 Part A Homework assignment, which gives you an opportunity to practice what you learned. These problems count for 10% of your total grade.   Wait until the end of the unit to attempt these problems. These problems help you identify the concepts that you have forgotten, and aid in long-term retention. These problems are mostly mechanical\u2013asking you to practice methods, and techniques learned in each unit. Each problem typically tests knowledge from only one section in a unit. (We won't necessarily tell you which one though!)    * **Part B Homework** Each unit has 1 Part B Homework assignment. The part B homework counts for 25% of your total grade.   The problems on this homework combine ideas from all of the sequences in the unit. These problems are mostly in the form of word problems which ask you to apply the methods learned to new scenarios.    * **Final** The final exam is offered only for veriried track learners. It is the culmination of your learning, and will account for 45% of your grade.   These problems cover all of the material in this course. Several of the problems follow the AP short-answer format. However, we cannot grade the justifications to your reasoning here. To prepare for the AP exam, you should take and review the solutions to sample AP exams from the AP website.  **What you need to know about the final exam**    * Only verified track learners have access to the final exam.     * The exam is timed. Once you open the exam, you have 48 hours to complete your work.     * The exam should take no more than 3 hours to complete if you have prepared by taking this course.     * If you begin the exam with less than 48 hours until the due date, you will not have the full 48 hours to complete the exam.     * Questions have infinite attempts, but you DO NOT receive any feedback on the correctness of your submission. (There is no green check or red X, only a note that your answer was submitted. Or an error message if it was not submitted.) So try to debug and check your work! If you find an error, you can resubmit without penalty. Only the final submission will be graded.     * There are no solutions provided to the exam.   **Use of forum during the final exam**    * We will leave the forum open since some people will be finishing Unit 4 while others are taking the exam.     * You may post about glitches, or other bugs/typos found in the exam.     * You may not post problem statements or parts of problem statements on the forum.     * DO NOT post hints, ask for hints, post parts of solutions. Doing so will result in being removed from the class, you will not receive a certificate, and you will not be able to access the archived course content.     * DO NOT work with others or collaborate, the work reflected should be your own.     * You may use notes or other memory aids, this exam is open book.   Grading", "filename": "logistics-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Grading"}

For example, if [mathjaxinline]\\, P(x)=-x^5-4x+1\\,[/mathjaxinline] then [mathjaxinline]\\mathrm{deg}(P)= 5.[/mathjaxinline]    royalblue **Rational functions** are ratios of polynomials. {"pageid": 116, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory2-tab7", "text": "So far, we have only defined and discussed definite integrals for [mathjaxinline]f\\geq 0[/mathjaxinline]. Geometrically, this is the area under the graph of [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline].  But what about definite integrals of general functions, which can be negative?    Recall the statement of FTC1:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(b)-F(a)\\qquad \\text {where}\\, \\, F'(x)=f(x),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.108)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Notice that the right hand side of the above equation, [mathjaxinline]F(b)-F(a)[/mathjaxinline], is still defined even if [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] is sometimes negative. This is because [mathjaxinline]F(x)[/mathjaxinline] is an antiderivative of [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline], and antiderivatives are defined for general functions, not only the non-negative ones.    Therefore, we can use this equation to define [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] for a general function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline]. That is, for **any** continuous function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline], let  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(b)-F(a),\\qquad \\text {where}\\, \\, F'(x)=f(x).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.109)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      In following problems, we will apply the equation in FTC1 to evaluate the definite integral of functions that can be negative somewhere. {"pageid": 119, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications4-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications4-tab3", "text": "To approximate the integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline]:    * Subdivide the interval into [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] pieces [mathjaxinline]a = x_0 < x_1 < \\dotsb < x_{n-1} < x_ n = b[/mathjaxinline].     * Let [mathjaxinline]y_0 = f(x_0)[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]y_1 = f(x_1)[/mathjaxinline], ... , [mathjaxinline]y_{n-1}= f(x_{n-1})[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]y_ n = f(x_ n)[/mathjaxinline].     * [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x = \\displaystyle \\frac{b-a}{n}[/mathjaxinline].     * **Left Riemann sum** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx \\approx \\Delta x\\left( y_0 + y_1 + \\dotsb + y_{n-1}\\right)[/mathjaxinline]     * **Right Riemann sum** [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx \\approx \\Delta x\\left( y_1 + y_2 + \\dotsb + y_ n\\right)[/mathjaxinline]   Riemann Sums: Left and Right", "filename": "applications4-tab3-text1.html", "title": "Riemann Sums: Left and Right"}

{"pageid": 124, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications1-tab2", "text": "### Objectives    * Apply Riemann integration to find bordeaux **areas bounded between curves**.     * Shift perspective between integrating with respect to [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] and integrating with respect to [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] depending on problem geometry.     * Apply Riemann integration to find bordeaux **volumes** of shapes whose cross-sectional area is known.     * Determine bordeaux **limits of integration** , and use the bordeaux **method of disks** , bordeaux **washers** , or bordeaux **shells** to determine bordeaux **volumes of revolution**.   ### Contents: 17 pages  13 videos (82 minutes at 1x speed) 24 problems  Objectives", "filename": "applications1-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 126, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory2-tab6", "text": "**Intuition: traveling in one direction**  Suppose you are traveling always in one direction between time [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline], and the velocity of your car at time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]v(t)\\geq 0[/mathjaxinline], and the position of your car at time [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline].    If you record your velocity every second. In other words, let [mathjaxinline]t_ i[/mathjaxinline] be the moment within the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] second when you read the speedometer, and [mathjaxinline]v(t_ i)[/mathjaxinline] be the velocity of your car at [mathjaxinline]t_ i[/mathjaxinline]. And let [mathjaxinline]\\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] be one second. Then [mathjaxinline]v(t_ i)\\cdot \\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] is an approximation of the distance travelled within the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] second, and when we add up all these small distances, we get an approximation of the total distance travelled in the entire journey.    |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\sum _{i=1}^{n} v(t_ i) \\cdot \\Delta t[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(b)-x(a) \\qquad (\\text {Riemann sum approximation}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.106)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      In other words, the Riemann sum **approximates** the total distance travelled by your car in the journey.  On the other hand, the first fundamental theorem says  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b v(t)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(b)-x(a) \\qquad (\\text {FTC1}).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.107)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      That is, the definite integral is **equal** to the total distance travelled in the whole journey.  Intuition", "filename": "theory2-tab6-text2.html", "title": "Intuition"}

To evaluate integrals with an even positive power of [mathjaxinline]\\sec[/mathjaxinline],  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int \\sec ^{2m}(x)\\tan ^ n(x)\\, dx\\qquad \\left(2m\\geq 2\\, \\, \\text {positive integer},\\, \\, n \\, \\text {real}\\right),[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.141)   ---|---|---|---      we can use substitution with [mathjaxinline]\\, u=\\tan (x),\\,[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\, du=\\sec ^2(x)\\, dx,\\,[/mathjaxinline]and then use the identity  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sec ^2(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle 1+\\tan ^2(x)\\qquad \\left(x\\neq \\frac{\\pi }{2}+k\\pi \\right)[/mathjaxinline] | | (4.142)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      to rewrite the integrand in terms of only [mathjaxinline]\\, u[/mathjaxinline].    Similarly, to evaluate integral with even positive power of [mathjaxinline]\\, \\csc[/mathjaxinline],  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int \\csc ^{2m}(x)\\cot ^ n(x)\\, dx\\qquad \\left(2m\\geq 2\\, \\, \\text {positive integer},\\, \\, n \\, \\text {real}\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.143)   ---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle .[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.144)      we can use the substitution [mathjaxinline]\\, u=\\cot (x)\\,[/mathjaxinline] and the identity  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\csc ^2(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\cot ^2(x)+1\\qquad \\left(x\\neq n\\pi \\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.145)   ---|---|---|---|---|---  Integral with even positive power of secant", "filename": "technique1-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Integral with even positive power of secant"}

{"pageid": 130, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_2-tab14", "text": "Let us summarize the rules of integration from the problems above, and make correspondence to the rules of differentiation.  |  Integration Rules |  Differentiation Rules   ---|---|---   Constant multiple: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int k \\, f (x) \\, dx \\, = \\, \\ k \\int \\, f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline]|  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle d(kF)\\, =\\, k\\, dF[/mathjaxinline]   Sum: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int \\left( f(x)+g(x) \\right)\\, dx =\\ \\int f(x)\\, dx +\\int g(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline]|  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle d(F+G)\\, =\\, dF+dG[/mathjaxinline]      On the other hand, the following naive product and quotient rules do NOT work.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int f\\cdot g\\, \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textbf{DOES NOT EQUAL}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ \\left( \\int \\, f \\, dx\\right)\\cdot \\left(\\int \\, g \\, dx\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int \\frac{f}{g} \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\textbf{DOES NOT EQUAL}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{ \\int f \\, dx }{ \\int g\\, dx}.[/mathjaxinline] |  |      The failure of this naive product rule corresponds to the fact that [mathjaxinline](FG)'\\neq (F')(G')[/mathjaxinline] and that we need the Leibniz rule for taking the derivative. Any quotient can be rewritten as a product, since [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{f}{g}=f \\cdot \\frac{1}{g}[/mathjaxinline], so the naive rule for quotient above does not hold for the same reason. In Unit 4, We will learn a technique called integration by parts which deals with integrals of products and is the integration analogue to the Leibniz rule.  How about the chain rule for differentiation? What is the integral version of the chain rule?  Summarize rules", "filename": "antider_2-tab14-text1.html", "title": "Summarize rules"}
