{"pageid": 133, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory2-tab8", "text": "**The definite integral of general functions**  Since the equation in the statement of FTC1 makes sense for general functions, we can use the FTC1 to extend the definition of the definite integral to functions that are not necessarily non-negative. That is:   For any continuous function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] with an antiderivative [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline],  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(b)-F(a)\\qquad \\left(\\text {for any continuous}\\, \\, f(x)=F'(x)\\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.116)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      It turns out that to be consistent with FTC1, the Riemann sum formula for definite integrals does not need to change. In other words, the definite integral of any continuous function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] (not necessarily non-negative), from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline], is  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(x) \\, dx\\, =\\, \\lim _{n\\rightarrow \\infty }\\, \\sum _{i=1}^{n} \\, f(c_ i) \\Delta x\\qquad (\\text {for any continuous}\\, \\, \\, f(x)).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Here, as before, [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Delta x= \\frac{b-a}{n}[/mathjaxinline] is the length of any one of the [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] subintervals that [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline] is divided into, and [mathjaxinline]c_ i[/mathjaxinline] is any point within the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] subinterval.    ![ ](/static/images/ftc1_Rimannnegative.svg)    The only difference from the case when [mathjaxinline]f\\geq 0[/mathjaxinline] is that [mathjaxinline]f(c_ i)[/mathjaxinline] can now also be negative. Therefore, [mathjaxinline]f(c_ i)[/mathjaxinline] is not just the height of the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] rectangle, but the height with a sign.    Consequently, the geometric definition of [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] that is consistent with FTC1 is as follows.  ![ ](/static/images/ftc1_signedarea.svg)   [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(x) \\, dx\\, =\\, \\text {Area above} \\, x\\text {-axis and below }\\, y=f(x)\\, -\\, \\text {Area below} \\, x\\text {-axis and above }\\, y=f(x)[/mathjax]|   ---|---      where the areas considered are between the vertical lines [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x=b[/mathjaxinline]. The important point is that the area above the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-axis is counted with a positive sign and the area below the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-axis is counted with a negative sign. In other words, the definite integral of a general function is the bordeaux **signed area bounded by the curve** bordeaux[mathjaxinline]y=f(x)[/mathjaxinline].    We will continue to use FTC1, not Riemann sums, to evaluate definite integrals. We will also often use the area interpretation to deduce properties of definite integrals, for example when looking for symmetry.  Definite integrals for general functions", "filename": "theory2-tab8-text1.html", "title": "Definite integrals for general functions"}

{"pageid": 134, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory2-tab2", "text": "**Objectives**    * Know the statement of the bordeaux **first fundamental theorem of calculus** and use it to evaluate definite integrals.     * Use bordeaux **properties of definite integrals** , such as additivity and symmetry, to set up and evaluate definite integrals.     * Use the bordeaux **method of substitution** to evaluate definite integrals.   **Contents: 22 pages**  11 videos (59 minutes 1x speed) 39 questions  Objectives", "filename": "theory2-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 135, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory3-tab7", "text": "**Proof of FTC2**  Recall that FTC2 states that given a continuous function [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline],  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(x)\\,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{x} f(t)\\, dt[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Rightarrow[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F'(x)=f(x).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.252)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      To prove this theorem, we will compute the derivative of [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline] by using the geometric picture of [mathjaxinline]F[/mathjaxinline]. We will prove the case for [mathjaxinline]f>0[/mathjaxinline] and you will verify that the same argument works for any [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline].    Recall the definition of the derivative:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle F'(x)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =\\lim _{\\Delta x\\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\Delta F}{\\Delta x} \\qquad \\text {where} \\, \\, \\Delta F\\, =\\, F(x+\\Delta x)-F(x).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.253)   ---|---|---|---|---   ![The area under a curve y equals f of t between t equals a and t equals x is F. The area under the curve y equals f of t between t equals x and t equals x plus Delta x is Delta F](/static/images/ftc2_proofFTC2.svg)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text {Geometrically,}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle F(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{x} f(t)\\, dt\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {Area between}\\, \\, a\\, \\, \\text {and}\\, \\, x,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.254)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Delta F[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{x}^{x+\\Delta x} f(t)\\, dt\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {Area between}\\, \\, x\\, \\, \\text {and}\\, \\, x+\\Delta x.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.255)      We can approximate [mathjaxinline]\\Delta F[/mathjaxinline] by the area of the rectangle with base [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x[/mathjaxinline] and height [mathjaxinline]\\, f(x)[/mathjaxinline]. This gives  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\frac{\\Delta F}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\approx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{f(x)\\cdot \\Delta x}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.256)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      Now since [mathjaxinline]f[/mathjaxinline] is continuous,  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\lim _{\\Delta x\\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\Delta F}{\\Delta x}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\lim _{\\Delta x\\rightarrow 0} f(x)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle f(x).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.257)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      This is equivalent to [mathjaxinline]F'(x)=f(x)[/mathjaxinline], which is what we needed to prove.  Proof of FTC2", "filename": "theory3-tab7-text2.html", "title": "Proof of FTC2"}

{"pageid": 136, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory2-tab13", "text": "If [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, f(x)\\leq g(x)[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]\\, a\\leq b,\\,[/mathjaxinline]then  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx\\, \\, \\, \\leq \\, \\, \\, \\int _{a}^{b} g(x)\\, dx \\qquad (\\text {for}\\, \\, a\\leq b).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Notice that the order of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] matters for this inequality. If [mathjaxinline]b \\leq a[/mathjaxinline], that is, the order of [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] are reversed, then since  [mathjax]\\displaystyle -\\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx\\, \\, \\, = \\, \\, \\, \\int _{b}^{a} f(x)\\, dx,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      and the second integral has the lower limit smaller than the upper limit, we can use the inequality above on the second integral.   This gives  [mathjax]-\\left(\\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx\\right)\\, \\, \\, = \\, \\, \\, \\int _{b}^{a} f(x)\\, dx\\, \\, \\, \\leq \\, \\, \\, \\int _{b}^{a} g(x)\\, dx\\, \\, \\, =\\, \\, \\, -\\left( \\int _{a}^{b} g(x)\\, dx \\right)\\qquad (b\\leq a).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Multiplying this inequality by [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline] and omitting two integrals in the middle, we get  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx\\, \\geq \\, \\int _{a}^{b} g(x)\\, dx \\qquad (b\\leq a).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      In other words, if the limits of the integrals are reversed, the inequality is also reversed.  Estimation", "filename": "theory2-tab13-text1.html", "title": "Estimation"}

{"pageid": 137, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@technique2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@technique2-tab5", "text": "**Worked example with trig substitution**   **Step**|  **Example**   ---|---   (1) Consider the integral: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int \\frac{dx}{x^2\\sqrt{1+x^2}}[/mathjaxinline]   (2) Identify ugliest part of integral: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sqrt{1+x^2}[/mathjaxinline]   (3) |  Make a substitution to simplify ugly expression:   ---   Based on [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sec ^2\\theta = 1+\\tan ^2\\theta[/mathjaxinline].   [mathjaxinline]\\begin{cases} x= \\tan \\theta \\\\\\ \\sqrt{1+x^2} = \\sqrt{\\sec ^2\\theta } = \\sec \\theta \\\\\\ dx = \\sec ^2\\theta \\, d\\theta \\end{cases}[/mathjaxinline]   (Note that generally, [mathjaxinline]\\sqrt{\\sec ^2\\theta } = |\\sec \\theta |[/mathjaxinline]. However, when we make the substituion [mathjaxinline]x = \\tan \\theta[/mathjaxinline], we are implicitly restricting to the range [mathjaxinline]-\\pi /2 < \\theta < \\pi /2[/mathjaxinline]. On this domain, [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] achieves all real values, [mathjaxinline]\\tan (\\theta )[/mathjaxinline] is continuous and invertible, and [mathjaxinline]\\sec (\\theta )>0[/mathjaxinline].) (4) Plug into integral: | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int \\frac{dx}{x^2\\sqrt{1+x^2}} = \\int \\frac{\\sec \\theta \\, d\\theta }{\\tan ^2 \\theta }[/mathjaxinline]   (5) Rewrite in terms of [mathjaxinline]\\sin[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\cos[/mathjaxinline]: |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\int \\frac{\\cos \\theta \\, d\\theta }{\\sin ^2 \\theta }[/mathjaxinline]   (6) Still not done. Need to evaluate this integral. |   How about trying a direct substitution? |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\begin{cases} u = \\sin \\theta \\\\\\ u^2 = \\sin ^2 \\theta \\\\\\ du = \\cos \\theta \\, d\\theta \\\\\\ \\end{cases}[/mathjaxinline]   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\int \\frac{du}{u^2}[/mathjaxinline]   (7) Evaluate the integral. |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{-1}{u}+C[/mathjaxinline]   This is the end of the calculus. |   (8) The rest is back substitution. |   First replace [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] by [mathjaxinline]\\sin \\theta[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]= \\displaystyle \\frac{-1}{\\sin \\theta } +C[/mathjaxinline]   (9) Draw a diagram of [mathjaxinline]x = \\tan \\theta[/mathjaxinline]: | ![Right triangle with one acute angle labeled theta. The side opposite theta is labeled x and the side adjacent to theta is labeled 1.](/static/images/trigsub_tri1.svg)   (10) Use diagram to determine [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\sin \\theta }[/mathjaxinline] in terms of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]: | ![Right triangle with one acute angle labeled theta. The side opposite theta is labeled x and the side adjacent to theta is labeled 1. The hypotenuse is labeled square root of 1 plus x squared.](/static/images/trigsub_tri2.svg)   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{\\sin \\theta } = \\frac{\\sqrt{1+x^2}}{x}[/mathjaxinline]   (11) Rewrite in terms of [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]: |  [mathjaxinline]= \\displaystyle -\\frac{\\sqrt{1+x^2}}{x} + C[/mathjaxinline]      The non-calculus part of this technique, the part of undoing the trig substitution, requires some practice. Note that in Steps (8), (9), and (10) we are actually computing the trig function of an inverse trig function. In our example, we had  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\theta[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\arctan x[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.295)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\csc \\theta[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\csc \\left(\\arctan x \\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.296)      Let's get some practice with this non-calculus component of the method now.  Trig substitution", "filename": "technique2-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Trig substitution"}

{"pageid": 139, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_1-tab15", "text": "**Bounding the average rate of change**  The MVT says that the average rate of change over an interval is equal to the derivative at some point in the interval. This implies that the average rate of change must be within the range of possible values of the derivative.    More precisely, if  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle m[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x'(c)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle M[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {for all}\\, \\, c\\, \\, \\text {with}\\, \\, a<c<b,[/mathjaxinline] |  | (1.97)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      that is, [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] is a lower bound and [mathjaxinline]M[/mathjaxinline] is an upper bound on [mathjaxinline]x'(c)[/mathjaxinline] over the interval [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline], then the MVT implies that  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle m[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{x(b)-x(a)}{b-a}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle M[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {(Bounds on the average rate of change).}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (1.98)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      In other words, a lower bound on the derivative is also a lower bound on the average rate of change, and an upper bound on the derivative is also an upper bound on the average rate of change.    Since [mathjaxinline]\\, (b-a)>0[/mathjaxinline], multiplying the inequality above of the average rate of change by [mathjaxinline]\\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline] will not change the inequality signs, and we get the following inequality of the total change of the function.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle m\\, \\cdot \\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(b)-x(a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle M \\, \\cdot \\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {(Bounds on the total change)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (1.99)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      In other words, the total change of the function from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] is greater than or equal to any lower bound [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] on the derivative over the interval [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline], times the length of the interval, [mathjaxinline](b-a)[/mathjaxinline]. And it is also less than or equal to any upper bound [mathjaxinline]M[/mathjaxinline] on the derivative over the interval [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline], times [mathjaxinline](b-a)[/mathjaxinline].    Sometimes we know the maximum and minimum values of [mathjaxinline]x'(t)[/mathjaxinline]. In this case, we can use the maximum as an upper bound and the minimum as a lower bound on [mathjaxinline]x'(t)[/mathjaxinline], and obtain the following inequality for the average rate of change.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\min _{a \\leq t \\leq b} x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{x(b)-x(a)}{b-a}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\max _{a\\leq t \\leq b} x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (1.100)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      Again multiplying both sides by [mathjaxinline]\\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline], we get an inequality on the total change of the function.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\min _{a \\leq t \\leq b} x'(t) \\, \\cdot \\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(b)-x(a)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\max _{a\\leq t \\leq b} x'(t) \\, \\cdot \\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (1.101)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      In other words, the average rate of change must be in between the maximum and the minimum of the derivative, and the total change must be in between the maximum and minimum of the derivative multiplied by the length of the interval.    Moreover, the maximum and minimum on [mathjaxinline]\\, x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] are the best bounds on [mathjaxinline]x'(t)[/mathjaxinline]. That is, for any upper bound [mathjaxinline]M[/mathjaxinline] and lower bound [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] on [mathjaxinline]\\, x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline],  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle m[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\min _{a \\leq t \\leq b} x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\max _{a\\leq t \\leq b} x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle M.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (1.102)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      In other words, the maximum is the least upper bound, the smallest number which is an upper bound, and the minimum is the greatest lower bound, the biggest number which is a lower bound.    The MVT then gives us the following inequalities for the average rate of change and the total change. For any upper bound [mathjaxinline]M[/mathjaxinline] and lower bound [mathjaxinline]m[/mathjaxinline] on the derivative [mathjaxinline]\\, x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline],  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle m[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\min _{a \\leq t \\leq b} x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{x(b)-x(a)}{b-a}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\max _{a\\leq t \\leq b} x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle M[/mathjaxinline] |  | (1.103)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle m\\, \\cdot \\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\min _{a \\leq t \\leq b} x'(t) \\, \\cdot \\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(b)-x(a)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\max _{a\\leq t \\leq b} x'(t)\\, \\cdot \\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\leq[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle M\\, \\cdot \\, (b-a)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (1.104)  Inequality with max and min", "filename": "antider_1-tab15-text1.html", "title": "Inequality with max and min"}

{"pageid": 144, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications3-tab4", "text": "Probability of picking a point randomly from a region, where all points are equally likely to be chosen is a weighted average.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle P(a< x <b) = \\frac{\\\\# \\text {Area of specified region}}{\\\\# \\text {Area entire region}} = \\frac{\\\\# \\text {Part}}{\\\\# \\text {Whole}} = \\frac{\\int _ a^ b(1-x^2)\\, dx }{\\int _{-1}^{1}(1-x^2)\\, dx }[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.25)   ---|---|---|---      Note this means that the probability is a real number [mathjaxinline]p[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\ 0\\leq p \\leq 1[/mathjaxinline]. The [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]- and [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline]- coordinates of the centroid are computed by the following integrals:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\bar{x}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{\\int _ a^ b x \\, dA}{\\int _ a^ b dA}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\qquad dA = y\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.15)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\bar{y}[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{\\int _ a^ b y\\, dA}{\\int _ a^ b dA}[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\qquad dA = x\\, dy[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.16)      We must define the limits of integration so that we integrate over the entire region with respect to [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]y[/mathjaxinline] respectively, and [mathjaxinline]dA[/mathjaxinline] is interpreted as the area of the infinitesimal vertical or horizontal rectangle respectively. {"pageid": 147, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_3-tab2", "text": "**Objectives**    * Recognize that first order royalblue **differential equations** describe a relationship between a function and its derivative, and that solutions are found using anti-differentiation.     * Use royalblue **separation of variables** to find royalblue **families of solution curves**.     * Solve differential equations with royalblue **initial conditions**.     * Draw and utilize royalblue **slope fields** of differential equations to gain qualitative understanding of solutions to differential equations.     * Use royalblue **Euler's Method** to approximate solutions to differential equations.   ### Contents: 13 pages  9 videos (40 minutes 1x speed) 20 questions 2 mathlets  Objectives", "filename": "antider_3-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 149, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory1-tab12", "text": "**Riemann sums**  Let us summarize in precise terms the steps for evaluating [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] using a Riemann Sum.      1. Divide [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline] into [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] equal subintervals.   ![ ](/static/images/defint_nintervals2.svg)  Then each interval is of length  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\Delta x= \\frac{b-a}{n}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Let the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] subinterval be the **base** of [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] rectangle.    2. Choose a point [mathjaxinline]c_ i[/mathjaxinline] within the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] subinterval.Choose [mathjaxinline]f(c_ i)[/mathjaxinline] be the **height** of the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] rectangle.    ![ ](/static/images/defint_ci2.svg)    3. Add up the areas of the [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] rectangles. The total area of [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] rectangles is:   [mathjax]\\underbrace{f(c_1)}_\\text {height}\\, \\underbrace{\\Delta x}_\\text {base} +\\underbrace{f(c_2)}_\\text {height} \\, \\underbrace{\\Delta x}_\\text {base}+\\cdots + \\underbrace{f(c_ n)}_\\text {height} \\underbrace{\\Delta x}_\\text {base} \\ =\\ \\sum _{i=1}^{n} f(c_ i) \\Delta x[/mathjax]|   ---|---     4. Take the limit as the rectangles become infinitesimally thin, ([mathjaxinline]\\Delta x \\rightarrow 0[/mathjaxinline], or equivalent [mathjaxinline]n\\rightarrow \\infty[/mathjaxinline]). This limit is the actual area under the curve between [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline].   [mathjax]\\lim _{n\\rightarrow \\infty }\\, \\sum _{i=1}^{n} \\, f(c_ i) \\Delta x\\ =\\ \\int _ a^ b f(x) \\, dx[/mathjax]|   ---|---    The sum of the areas of the [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] rectangles, [mathjaxinline]\\sum _{i=1}^{n} f(c_ i) \\Delta x[/mathjaxinline], is called a royalblue **Riemann Sum**. If we pick [mathjaxinline]c_ i[/mathjaxinline] to be the left endpoint of the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] subinterval, the Riemann sum is called a royalblue **left Riemann Sum**. Similarly, if [mathjaxinline]c_ i[/mathjaxinline] is the right endpoint of the [mathjaxinline]i^{\\text {th}}[/mathjaxinline] interval, the Riemann sum is called a royalblue **right Riemann sum**.    However, in the limit [mathjaxinline]n\\rightarrow \\infty[/mathjaxinline] (so that [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x\\rightarrow 0[/mathjaxinline]), this distinction is no longer needed. The limit of any Riemann Sum, no matter what the [mathjaxinline]c_ i[/mathjaxinline]'s within the subinterval are, is equal to the exact area under the curve.    Riemann sum", "filename": "theory1-tab12-text1.html", "title": "Riemann sum"}

{"pageid": 154, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@technique2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@technique2-tab2", "text": "**Objectives**    * Use royalblue **trigonometric substitution** to evaluate integrands that contain [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sqrt{a^2-x^2}\\,[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sqrt{a^2+x^2}\\,[/mathjaxinline], and [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\sqrt{x^2-a^2}\\, .[/mathjaxinline]     * Use the method of royalblue **completing the square** to manipulate integrals into one of the above forms, and perform a trig substitution.   **Contents: 10 pages**  7 videos (57 minutes 1x speed) 13 questions  Objectives", "filename": "technique2-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Objectives"}

{"pageid": 155, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications2-tab9", "text": "### 1-dimensional center of mass  For a 1-dimensional rod of length [mathjaxinline]L[/mathjaxinline] with linear density function [mathjaxinline]\\lambda (x)[/mathjaxinline] (measured in mass per unit length), the center of mass is the weighted average:  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\bar{x} = \\frac{\\int _0^ L x \\lambda (x)\\, dx}{\\int _0^ L \\lambda (x)\\, dx}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Center of mass", "filename": "applications2-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Center of mass"}

{"pageid": 156, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@extra-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@extra-tab4", "text": "We now return to find a general formula for [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, \\displaystyle \\int \\cos ^{2m+1} (x) \\sin ^ n(x)\\, dx,\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] when [mathjaxinline]\\, 2m+1\\,[/mathjaxinline] is an odd positive integer, and [mathjaxinline]\\, n\\neq -(2k+1)[/mathjaxinline] for any integer [mathjaxinline]\\, 0\\leq k\\leq m.\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline]  General formula for the integral of odd powers", "filename": "extra-tab4-text1.html", "title": "General formula for the integral of odd powers"}

{"pageid": 157, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications3-tab11", "text": "[PDF Version](/static/pdf/probability_summary.pdf)   **Discrete probability**  Discrete probability measures the likelihood of a specified outcome.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\text {Discrete Probability} = \\frac{\\\\# \\text { specified outcomes}}{\\\\# \\text { all possible outcomes}}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.65)   ---|---|---|---      Note this means that the probability is a positive fraction that is less than or equal to [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline].  **Distributions**  A royalblue **distribution** is a nonnegative function [mathjaxinline]w(x)[/mathjaxinline] that approximates the discrete distribution. The area under a distribution measures the probability that an event occurs.  [mathjax]\\displaystyle P(a < x < b) = \\frac{\\int _ a^ b w(x)\\, dx}{\\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } w(x)\\, dx}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      For commonly used distributions, it is common to rescale the function. Since [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } w(x)\\, dx =C[/mathjaxinline] is a finite constant, we define a new function [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle p(x) = \\frac{w(x)}{C}[/mathjaxinline]. This new function [mathjaxinline]p(x)[/mathjaxinline] had the property that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } p(x)\\, dx =1[/mathjaxinline].  A royalblue **probability distribution** or a royalblue **probability density function** is defined as a nonnegative function [mathjaxinline]p(x)[/mathjaxinline] defined on [mathjaxinline]-\\infty < x < \\infty[/mathjaxinline] with the property that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } p(x)\\, dx =1[/mathjaxinline]. In this case, the probability of the outcome [mathjaxinline]a<x<b[/mathjaxinline] is defined as:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle P(a < x < b)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b p(x)\\, dx.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.66)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      ### Normal distribution  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle p(x) = \\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{2\\pi }} e^{\\frac{-(x-\\mu )^2}{2\\sigma ^2}},[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\qquad -\\infty < x < \\infty ,[/mathjaxinline] | | (3.67)   ---|---|---|---|---      where the expected value is [mathjaxinline]\\mu[/mathjaxinline] and the standard deviation is [mathjaxinline]\\sigma[/mathjaxinline].  The normal distribution is used to compute probabilities across all sciences, social sciences, and engineering, for example in measurements in astronomy, biology, chemistry, or physics. You may have seen it used for grades on an exam, or with respect to heights or weights of people in a population.  ### Exponential distribution  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle p(t) = a e^{-a t}, \\quad 0 \\leq t < \\infty[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\qquad \\text {(and }p(t) = 0, \\quad t<0\\text {)},[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.68)   ---|---|---|---|---      where the expected value is [mathjaxinline]1/a[/mathjaxinline].  Note that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _0^{\\infty } a e^{-a t} \\, dt =1[/mathjaxinline], so this is a probability distribution. The exponential distribution is used to compute the probability of a \u201cwaiting time\" between events, such as the arrival of a bus, the decay of a radioactive particle, or the time between phone calls during business hours.  **Expected Value**  Given a probability distribution [mathjaxinline]p(x)[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } p(x)\\, dx =1[/mathjaxinline], the royalblue **expected value** , [mathjaxinline]E[/mathjaxinline], also known as the royalblue **mean**.  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\text {Expected value} = E= \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } x p(x)\\, dx.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Note that the expected value is completely analogous to _center of mass_. Here we do not need to divide by the total integral of the probability distribution since the integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } p(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] is normalized to be equal to [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]  **Variance**  Given a probability distribution [mathjaxinline]p(x)[/mathjaxinline] with [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } p(x)\\, dx =1[/mathjaxinline], and whose expected value is [mathjaxinline]E[/mathjaxinline], the royalblue **variance** , [mathjaxinline]V[/mathjaxinline], measures the average spread of outcomes from the expected value.  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\text {Variance}= V = \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } (x-E)^2 p(x)\\, dx.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      The royalblue **standard deviation** , [mathjaxinline]\\sigma[/mathjaxinline], is the square root of the variance:  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\sigma = \\sqrt{V}.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      **Area under the bell curve**  The area under half of the bell curve is  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{0}^{\\infty }e^{-x^2}\\, dx = \\sqrt{\\pi }/2.[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Summary", "filename": "applications3-tab11-text1.html", "title": "Summary"}

{"pageid": 158, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_1-tab5", "text": "#### Proof of MVT  To prove the Mean Value Theorem, we will start by proving a special case in which the function has the same values at the two end points, and then use this special case to prove the full theorem.    To prove the special case, we will rely on the royalblue **Extreme Value Theorem** , which says that any function which is continuous on a closed interval must attain both its maximum and minimum values in that closed interval.   This theorem requires deeper analysis of the real numbers and we will not prove it here. The point is that we need continuity to guarantee that the function attains both its maximum and minimum.     **Proof of the special case**  Suppose a function [mathjaxinline]x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline] satisfies the hypothesis of the MVT, that is, [mathjaxinline]x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline] is continuous on [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], and differentiable on [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline].    In this special case, suppose also that [mathjaxinline]x_0(a)=x_0(b)[/mathjaxinline]. By the Extreme Value Theorem, [mathjaxinline]x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline] attains both its maximum and minimum in [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline]. In other words, there is at least one point [mathjaxinline]t_1[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ x_0(t_1)\\, =\\, \\min _{a\\leq t\\leq b} x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline], and at least one point [mathjaxinline]t_2[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ x_0(t_2)\\, =\\, \\max _{a\\leq t\\leq b} x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline].    There are only two possibilities. The maximum and minimum are either equal or not.    Case 1: [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ \\max _{a\\leq t\\leq b} x_0(t)\\, =\\, \\min _{a\\leq t\\leq b} x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline]        [mathjaxinline]x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline] must be constant over [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]x'_0(t)=0[/mathjaxinline] for all [mathjaxinline]a<t<b[/mathjaxinline]. In particular, there is at least one point [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline], with [mathjaxinline]a<c<b[/mathjaxinline] at which [mathjaxinline]x'_0(c)=0[/mathjaxinline].  Case 2: [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\ \\max _{a\\leq t\\leq b} x_0(t)\\, \\neq \\min _{a\\leq t\\leq b} x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline]        Since [mathjaxinline]x_0(a)=x_0(b)[/mathjaxinline], they cannot both be at the end points. Hence at least one of [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\max _{a\\leq t\\leq b} x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\, \\min _{a\\leq t\\leq b} x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline] must be achieved in [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline]. Hence, there must be a [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline], with [mathjaxinline]a<c<b[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]x_0(c)=\\max _{a\\leq t\\leq b} x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline] or [mathjaxinline]x_0(c)=\\min _{a\\leq t\\leq b} x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline]. Now, recall the derivative of a differentiable function at a local maximum or minimum. By the hypothesis, [mathjaxinline]x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline] is differentiable in [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline], so [mathjaxinline]x'_0(c)=0[/mathjaxinline] since [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] is either a local maximum or a minimum.  In both cases, there is a point [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline], with [mathjaxinline]a<c<b[/mathjaxinline], such that  [mathjax]\\displaystyle x'_0(c)\\, =\\, 0 \\, =\\, \\frac{0}{b-a} \\, =\\, \\frac{x_0(b)-x_0(a)}{b-a}\\qquad \\textrm{since}\\, x_0(a)=x_0(b).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This special case of the MVT is called royalblue **Rolle's Theorem.**    Let us now use the special case above to prove the MVT for functions with possibly different endpoint values.  Suppose a function [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] satisfies the hypothesis of the MVT, that is, [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is continuous on [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], and differentiable on [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline]. Let  [mathjax]\\displaystyle x_0(t)\\, =\\, x(t)-\\left(x(a)+ \\frac{x(b)-x(a)}{b-a}(t-a)\\right).[/mathjax]|   ---|---      That is, construct a function [mathjaxinline]x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline] by subtracting from [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] the line that goes through [mathjaxinline](a,x(a))[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline](b,x(b))[/mathjaxinline]. Then [mathjaxinline]x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline] also satisfies the hypothesis of the MVT, and [mathjaxinline]x_0(a)=x_0(b)=0[/mathjaxinline]. So we can apply Rolle's Theorem to [mathjaxinline]x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline], and know that there is a [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline](a, b)[/mathjaxinline], such that [mathjaxinline]x_0'(c)=0[/mathjaxinline].   Now we can rearrange the equation above and get [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] in terms of [mathjaxinline]x_0(t)[/mathjaxinline].  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_0(t)+ \\left(x(a)+ \\frac{x(b)-x(a)}{b-a}(t-a)\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---      Taking the derivative on both sides. we get  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_0'(t)\\, + \\, \\frac{x(b)-x(a)}{b-a}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---      And at the point [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] in [mathjaxinline](a,b)[/mathjaxinline] at which [mathjaxinline]x_0'(c)=0[/mathjaxinline], the equation above reduces to  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x'(c)[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle x_0'(c)+ \\frac{x(b)-x(a)}{b-a}[/mathjaxinline] |  |   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{x(b)-x(a)}{b-a}[/mathjaxinline] |  |      Thus, we have found a [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] we need for the conclusion of the MVT.  [Show](javascript: {return false;})   **Supplementary link:** There is a nice visualization tool @EmilyMcKee made; the tool lets you explore what the existence of [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline], explained in this proof, actually looks like when visualized in a graphic. The tool is at [this link](https://www.desmos.com/calculator/vdhfhltxcr), it was made using Desmos graphing calculator and enables you to play with it changing the parameters as you wish.  Proof", "filename": "antider_1-tab5-text2.html", "title": "Proof"}

We choose  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u\\, =\\, x^2[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ,[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v'\\, =\\, x\\, \\cos \\left(x^2\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.470)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u'\\, =\\, 2x[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ,[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v\\, =\\, \\frac{\\sin \\left(x^2\\right)}{2}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.471)      Integrating by parts, we have  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int \\underbrace{x^2}_ u \\, \\, \\underbrace{x\\cos \\left(x^2\\right)}_{v'}\\, dx\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\underbrace{x^2}_{u}\\, \\, \\underbrace{\\frac{\\sin \\left(x^2\\right)}{2}}_{v} - \\int \\underbrace{\\frac{\\sin \\left(x^2\\right)}{2}}_{v}\\, \\, \\underbrace{2x}_{u'}\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.472)   ---|---|---|---|---   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle = \\frac{x^2 \\sin \\left(x^2\\right)}{2}+ \\frac{\\cos \\left(x^2\\right)}{2}+C.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.473)      How did we choose [mathjaxinline]\\, u\\,[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]\\, v'\\,[/mathjaxinline]? The short answer is that we chose the one that worked!    The longer answer is as follows. First, look at the most complicated function [mathjaxinline]\\, \\cos \\left(x^2\\right),\\,[/mathjaxinline] in the integrand, if we set [mathjaxinline]\\, u\\, =\\, \\cos \\left(x^2\\right),\\,[/mathjaxinline] then  |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u\\, =\\, \\cos \\left(x^2\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ,[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v'\\, =\\, x^3[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.474)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle u'\\, =\\, - 2x\\, \\sin \\left(x^2\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle ,[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v\\, =\\, \\frac{x^4}{4}.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.475)      The derivative of [mathjaxinline]\\, u,\\,[/mathjaxinline] is complicated and we check that [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\int u' v \\, dx\\,[/mathjaxinline] is also more complicated than the original integral:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int u'v\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int 2x\\, \\sin \\left(x^2\\right)\\, \\left(\\frac{x^4}{4}\\right)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\frac{1}{2}\\, \\int x^5\\, \\sin \\left(x^2\\right)\\, dx.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.476)   ---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---      Next, we try [mathjaxinline]\\, v'=\\cos \\left(x^2\\right),\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] but we cannot integrate it easily. However, we do know how to integrate [mathjaxinline]\\, x\\cos \\left(x^2\\right).\\, \\,[/mathjaxinline] Therefore, the trick is to choose  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v'\\, =\\, x\\cos \\left(x^2\\right)[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\Longrightarrow[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle v\\, =\\, \\frac{1}{2} \\sin \\left(x^2\\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.477)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Once this choice is made, the rest of the procedure is mechanical and as above.     **Note:** Recall [mathjaxinline]\\, \\displaystyle \\int \\cos (x^2)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] is the Fresnel integral and cannot be expressed in terms of elementary functions. {"pageid": 164, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory2-tab19", "text": "**Caution for the method of substitution**  When we use the method of substitution, we need to be very careful about when [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline] (or [mathjaxinline]du[/mathjaxinline]) changes sign. If [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline] changes sign within the integration interval [mathjaxinline][a,b][/mathjaxinline], the method of substitution may give the wrong answer. In this case, we need to first rewrite the integral as a sum of two integrals such that within the limits of each integral [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline] does not change sign, and then use the method of substitution on each integral separately.     **Example: [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-1}^{1} x^2\\, dx[/mathjaxinline]**  Here is an example to show what goes wrong and how to use the method of substitution correctly if [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline] changes sign within the limits of the integral. It is just for illustrative purpose because we can easily compute this integral without using the method of substitution.  First, [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-1}^{1} x^2 \\, dx \\neq 0[/mathjaxinline] by direct computation using FTC1 or by the fact that the area under [mathjaxinline]y=x^2[/mathjaxinline] between [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline] is non- zero.    On the other hand, if we use the method of substitution and let [mathjaxinline]u=x^2[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]du=2x\\, dx[/mathjaxinline]. Notice [mathjaxinline]du[/mathjaxinline] changes sign at [mathjaxinline]x=0[/mathjaxinline], which is between the lower and upper limits of the integral. Now, if we make the mistake of applying substitution directly, we get  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _{-1}^{1} x^2 \\, dx = \\int _{u=(-1)^2}^{u=1^2} u \\cdot \\frac{du}{2\\sqrt{u}} = \\int _{1}^{1} u \\cdot \\frac{du}{2\\sqrt{u}}=0[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This is clearly incorrect.     **Using substitution correctly**  To use the substitution [mathjaxinline]u=x^2[/mathjaxinline] correctly, we need to first break the integral into two pieces so that [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline] does not change sign within the limits of each of the two integral. Since [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline] changes sign at [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline], we will break the integral into two at [mathjaxinline]0[/mathjaxinline].  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle \\int _{-1}^{1} x^2 \\, dx[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-1}^{0} x^2 \\, dx + \\int _{0}^{1} x^2 \\, dx.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (2.167)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Then, since [mathjaxinline]x^2[/mathjaxinline] is even, [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-1}^{1} x^2 \\, dx =2 \\int _{0}^{1} x^2 \\, dx[/mathjaxinline]. Since [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline] does not change sign within [mathjaxinline][0,1][/mathjaxinline], we can use the method of substitution with [mathjaxinline]u=x^2[/mathjaxinline] on [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{0}^{1} x^2 \\, dx[/mathjaxinline].  [mathjax]\\left.\\int _{0}^{1} x^2 \\, dx = \\int _{(0)^2}^{1^2} u \\cdot \\frac{du}{2\\sqrt{u}} = \\frac{1}{2}\\left(\\frac{2}{3}u^{\\frac{3}{2}}\\right) \\right|_{0}^{1}= \\frac{1}{3}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      This gives [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-1}^{1} x^2 \\, dx =\\frac{2}{3}[/mathjaxinline], which is the correct answer.     **Explanation**  So what went wrong when we apply this substitution [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-1}^{1} x^2 \\, dx[/mathjaxinline]? What happens is that when [mathjaxinline]u'[/mathjaxinline] changes sign, [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] must be sometimes increasing and sometimes decreasing. But this means that [mathjaxinline]u(x)[/mathjaxinline] does not have a well-defined inverse. That is, there is not one formula [mathjaxinline]x=x(u)[/mathjaxinline] that works in the whole interval of integration. In this example,  [mathjax]\\displaystyle x\\, \\, = \\, \\, \\begin{cases} \\displaystyle +\\sqrt{u} & \\mbox{if } x \\geq 0 \\\\\\ -\\sqrt{u} & \\mbox{if } x\\leq 0. \\end{cases}[/mathjax]| (2.168)   ---|---      If we first break the region of integration into regions for which the inverse of [mathjaxinline]u[/mathjaxinline] is well-defined, the method of substitution can be used in each region.  Warning on the method of substitution", "filename": "theory2-tab19-text1.html", "title": "Warning on the method of substitution"}

{"pageid": 165, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory1-tab3", "text": "**The geometric definition of the definite integral**  We will only deal with definite integrals of non-negative functions in this section.    Geometrically, the bordeaux **definite integral of [mathjaxinline]f\\,[/mathjaxinline] from [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] to [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline]** , denoted by  [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\int _ a^ b f(x)\\, dx,[/mathjax]|   ---|---      is the area under the graph of [mathjaxinline]f(x)[/mathjaxinline] between [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline].  ![A function y equals f of x is plotted in the first quadrant. The points a and b are indicated on the x axis. The region beneath the function and between the vertical lines x equals a and x equals b is shaded.](/static/images/defint_riemann4.svg)  More precisely, this definite integral is equal to the area of the region above the [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-axis, below the curve [mathjaxinline]y=f(x)[/mathjaxinline], and in between the two vertical lines [mathjaxinline]x=a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]x=b[/mathjaxinline], as shown shaded in the figure below.  The [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline]-values [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline] are called the bordeaux **lower and upper limits of the integral**. (This is a different sense of the word \"limit\" from when we take a limit of a function.)    The only difference between the notation for definite and indefinite integrals is that definite integrals have limits but indefinite integrals do not. {"pageid": 171, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications3-tab6", "text": "Recall that a probability distribution is a non-negative function [mathjaxinline]p(x)[/mathjaxinline] such that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } p(x)\\, dx =1[/mathjaxinline]. The royalblue **expected value** , [mathjaxinline]E[/mathjaxinline], also known as the royalblue **mean** is defined by:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle E[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } x p(x)\\, dx.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.42)   ---|---|---|---|---|---      Note that the expected value is completely analogous to _center of mass_. Here we do not need to divide by the total integral of the probability distribution since the integral [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } p(x)\\, dx[/mathjaxinline] is normalized to be equal to [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]. {"pageid": 172, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@applications3-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@applications3-tab5", "text": "A royalblue **distribution** is a nonnegative function [mathjaxinline]w(x)[/mathjaxinline] that approximates the discrete distribution. The area under a distribution is proportional to the probability that an event occurs.  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle P(a < x < b) = \\frac{\\int _ a^ b w(x)\\, dx}{\\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } w(x)\\, dx}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.26)   ---|---|---|---      For commonly used distributions, it is common to rescale the function. Since [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } w(x)\\, dx =C[/mathjaxinline] is a finite constant, we define a new function [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle p(x) = \\frac{w(x)}{C}[/mathjaxinline]. This new function [mathjaxinline]p(x)[/mathjaxinline] had the property that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } p(x)\\, dx =1[/mathjaxinline].  A royalblue **probability distribution** or a royalblue **probability density function** is defined as a nonnegative function [mathjaxinline]p(x)[/mathjaxinline] defined on [mathjaxinline]-\\infty < x < \\infty[/mathjaxinline] with the property that [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _{-\\infty }^{\\infty } p(x)\\, dx =1[/mathjaxinline]. In this case, the probability of the outcome [mathjaxinline]a<x<b[/mathjaxinline] is defined as:  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle P(a < x < b) = \\int _ a^ b p(x)\\, dx.[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.27)   ---|---|---|---      ### royalblueNormal distribution  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle p(x) = \\frac{1}{\\sigma \\sqrt{2\\pi }} e^{\\frac{-(x-\\mu )^2}{2\\sigma ^2}},[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\qquad -\\infty < x < \\infty[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.28)   ---|---|---|---|---      The normal distribution is used to compute probabilities across all sciences, social sciences, and engineering, for example in measurements in astronomy, biology, chemistry, or physics. You may have seen it used for grades on an exam, or with respect to heights or weights of people in a population.  ### royalblueExponential distribution  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle p(t) = a e^{-a t}, \\quad 0 \\leq t < \\infty[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\qquad \\text {(and }p(t) = 0, \\quad t<0\\text {)}[/mathjaxinline] |  | (3.29)   ---|---|---|---|---      This is a probability distribution as [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\int _0^{\\infty } a e^{-a t} \\, dt =1[/mathjaxinline]. The exponential distribution is used to compute the probability of a \u201cwaiting time\" between events, such as the arrival of a bus, the decay of a radioactive particle, or the time between phone calls during business hours.  Distributions", "filename": "applications3-tab5-text2.html", "title": "Distributions"}

{"pageid": 173, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@technique2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@technique2-tab9", "text": "**Video note:** There is an absolute value sign missing inside the logarithm at 8:38 onwards.     **Completing the square**  We use completing the square to rewrite any quadratic function into a form which is more conducive to using trigonometric substitution.    To complete the square means to rewrite any quadratic function [mathjaxinline]\\, Ax^2+Bx+C\\,[/mathjaxinline] into the form [mathjaxinline]\\, A(x+b)^2+c[/mathjaxinline].    Here is the algebra:    |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\displaystyle Ax^2+Bx+C[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A\\left(x^2+\\frac{B}{A}x \\right)+C \\qquad \\text {Factor out }\\, A[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.355)   ---|---|---|---|---|---   |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle \\text {Add and subtract the square term}\\qquad[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A\\left(x^2+\\frac{B}{A}x+ \\left(\\frac{B}{2A} \\right)^2 \\right) - A\\left(\\frac{B}{2A} \\right)^2+C[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.356)   |  |  [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle =[/mathjaxinline] | [mathjaxinline]\\displaystyle A\\left(x+\\frac{B}{2A} \\right)^2 +\\left(-\\frac{B^2}{4A}+C\\right).[/mathjaxinline] |  | (4.357)  Completing the square", "filename": "technique2-tab9-text1.html", "title": "Completing the square"}

{"pageid": 176, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@antider_1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@antider_1-tab5", "text": "If [mathjaxinline]x(t)[/mathjaxinline] is continuous on [mathjaxinline]a\\leq t \\leq b[/mathjaxinline], and differentiable on [mathjaxinline]a<t<b[/mathjaxinline], that is, [mathjaxinline]x'(t)[/mathjaxinline] is defined for all [mathjaxinline]t[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]\\, \\, a<t<b[/mathjaxinline], then    [mathjax]\\displaystyle \\frac{x(b)-x(a)}{b-a} \\, = x'(c) \\qquad \\text {for some }c,\\, \\, \\text {with } a<c<b.[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Equivalently, in geometric terms, there is at least one point [mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline], with [mathjaxinline]a<c<b[/mathjaxinline], at which the tangent line is parallel to the secant line through [mathjaxinline](a, x(a))[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline](b, x(b))[/mathjaxinline]:  ![An increasing, concave down curve is plotted in the x versus t plane. The tangent line to the graph is drawn at c comma x of c.](/static/images/antider1_xtgraph_MVT_statement.svg)  Statement of Mean Value Theorem", "filename": "antider_1-tab5-text1.html", "title": "Statement of Mean Value Theorem"}

{"pageid": 177, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory2-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory2-tab11", "text": "**Properties of definite integrals**  Here are some properties of definite integrals. We have discussed and used most of these properties for [mathjaxinline]f>0[/mathjaxinline]. The properties below are true for definite integrals for functions which can be negative as well.  Sums:      [mathjax]\\int _{a}^{b} \\left( f(x) +g(x) \\right) \\, dx \\, =\\, \\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx +\\int _{a}^{b} g(x) \\, dx[/mathjax]|    ---|---   Constant Multiples:      [mathjax]\\int _{a}^{b} c \\, f(x) \\, dx \\, =\\, c\\, \\int _{a}^{b} f(x)\\, dx\\qquad \\text {for any constant}\\, c[/mathjax]|    ---|---   Same Upper and Lower Limits:      [mathjax]\\int _{a}^{a} \\, f(x) \\, dx\\, =\\, 0[/mathjax]|    ---|---   Reversing Limits of Integrals:      [mathjax]\\int _{b}^{a} \\, f(x) \\, dx\\, =\\, - \\int _{a}^{b} \\, f(x) \\, dx\\qquad \\text {for any}\\, a,b[/mathjax]|    ---|---      This is the definition of a definite integral with its lower limit greater than its upper limit. It is defined this way to be consistent with FTC1.  Combining integrals:      [mathjax]\\int _{a}^{c} \\, f(x) \\, dx\\, =\\, \\int _{a}^{b} \\, f(x) \\, dx\\, +\\, \\int _{b}^{c} \\, f(x) \\, dx\\qquad \\text {for any}\\, a,b,c[/mathjax]|    ---|---      Notice that we can use this property with [mathjaxinline]a[/mathjaxinline],[mathjaxinline]b[/mathjaxinline],[mathjaxinline]c[/mathjaxinline] in any order.  Properties of integrals", "filename": "theory2-tab11-text1.html", "title": "Properties of integrals"}

{"pageid": 178, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@theory1-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@theory1-tab14", "text": "Limit of sums can be very hard to evaluate. Recognizing a limit of sums as the limit of a Riemann sum allows us to evaluate the limit as the integral.    **Example problem:** Consider the right Riemann sum  [mathjax]\\sum _{i=1}^{n} \\frac{2}{n} \\left(-1+\\frac{2i}{n}\\right)^3[/mathjax]|   ---|---      Express the limit  [mathjax]\\lim _{n\\rightarrow \\infty } \\sum _{i=1}^{n} \\frac{2}{n} \\left(-1+\\frac{2i}{n}\\right)^3[/mathjax]|   ---|---      as a definite integral.  **orangeSolution:** Let's evaluate the expressions inside the sum.  [mathjax]\\sum _{i=1}^{n} \\frac{2}{n} \\left(-1+\\frac{2i}{n}\\right)^3[/mathjax]|   ---|---      We want to write this sum in terms of a multiple [mathjaxinline]{\\color {orange}{\\Delta x}}[/mathjaxinline] that is independent of the index [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline] and a function [mathjaxinline]{\\color {blue}{f(x)}}[/mathjaxinline] which should contain all of the terms involving the index [mathjaxinline]i[/mathjaxinline]. In our case  [mathjax]{\\color {orange}{\\frac{2}{n}}} {\\color {blue}{\\left(-1+\\frac{2i}{n}\\right)^3}} = {\\color {orange}{\\Delta x}} {\\color {blue}{ f(x)}}[/mathjax]|   ---|---      At this stage what do we know? Since [mathjaxinline]\\Delta x = 2/n[/mathjaxinline], the width of each rectangle is [mathjaxinline]2/n[/mathjaxinline] and we are summing over [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] rectangles. Therefore the total length of the interval we are summing over is [mathjaxinline]n\\cdot 2/n = 2[/mathjaxinline].  To determine the upper and lower limit of the definite integral, first we need to figure out what our function is. In this case it seems that  [mathjax]\\left(-1+\\frac{2i}{n}\\right)^3 = f(-1+\\frac{2i}{n}) = f(x) = x^3[/mathjax]|   ---|---      so our function is that we are integrating is [mathjaxinline]f(x) = x^3[/mathjaxinline], and our expression for [mathjaxinline]x[/mathjaxinline] is [mathjaxinline]-1 +2i/n[/mathjaxinline]. In particular, when [mathjaxinline]i=1[/mathjaxinline], [mathjaxinline]x=-1+2/n[/mathjaxinline]. As [mathjaxinline]n[/mathjaxinline] tends to infinity, this becomes [mathjaxinline]x=-1[/mathjaxinline]. So the lower limit of the integral is [mathjaxinline]-1[/mathjaxinline]. When [mathjaxinline]i=n[/mathjaxinline], then [mathjaxinline]x=-1+2n/n = 1[/mathjaxinline]. Therefore the upper limit of the definite integral is [mathjaxinline]1[/mathjaxinline]. This confirms what we discovered earlier, the length of the integral we are integrating over is [mathjaxinline]1 - (-1) = 2[/mathjaxinline].  Therefore the limit of this sum represents the definite integral  [mathjax]\\int _{-1}^{1} x^3 \\, dx \\, .[/mathjax]|   ---|---  Worked example", "filename": "theory1-tab14-text1.html", "title": "Worked example"}

{"pageid": 179, "url": "https://learning.edx.org/course/course-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@sequential+block@logistics-sequential/block-v1:MITx+18.01.2x+3T2022+type@vertical+block@logistics-tab2", "text": "Discover the integral\u2014what it is and how to compute it. See how to use calculus to model real world phenomena. Part 2 of 3.  How long should the handle of your spoon be so that your fingers do not burn while mixing chocolate fondue? Can you find a shape that has finite volume, but infinite surface area? How does the weight of the rider change the trajectory of a zip line ride? These and many other questions can be answered by harnessing the power of the integral. But what is an integral? You will learn to interpret it geometrically as an area under a graph, and discover its connection to the derivative. You will encounter functions that you cannot integrate without a computer and develop a big bag of tricks to attack the functions that you can integrate by hand. The integral is vital in engineering design, scientific analysis, probability and statistics. You will use integrals to find centers of mass, the stress on a beam during construction, the power exerted by a motor, and the distance traveled by a rocket.  This course, in combination with 18.01.1x Calculus 1A: Differentiation, covers the AP Calculus AB curriculum. This course, in combination with 18.01.1x Calculus 1A: Differentiation and 18.01.3x Calculus 1C: Coordinate Systems and Infinite Series, covers the AP Calculus BC curriculum. If you intend to take an AP exam, we strongly suggest that you familiarize yourself with the AP exam to prepare for it.  Course Description", "filename": "logistics-tab2-text1.html", "title": "Course Description"}
